animal.description:
My name is MOCHA and I'm a gorgeous 7 yr F Tan/White Amstaff. I'm 70 lbs of BIG LOVE!! My owners had to move to a new home due to COVID hardship and now the landlord says I have to go!!  I'm a sweet chunky mama that had a very rough start in life. I was used as a bait dog as a puppy and luckily was rescued before I was torn to bits; however the scars were deep and as a result I am NOT FOND OF DOGS!  I've had a few altercations with dogs in the past so I need to be a SOLO DOG.  Funny enough I'm ok with cats as I'm living with cats now.  I've never been around young kids but because of my size... ages 13 yrs+ would be best. I'm a chubba wubba because I'm not getting enough daily exercise and my mama spoils me with chicken mcnugget treats ....but all the more dog to love! and I am a COMPLETE SNUGGLEBUG!! I have to snuggle under the covers with you!!  I love people and get very excited to meet them and sometimes I can be jumpy and mouthy because I can't contain my excitement so I will need further training with that. I'm looking for an ADULT ONLY quiet home in the suburbs with patient humans that are EXPERIENCED DOG HANDLERS &  KNOW, UNDERSTAND and APPRECIATE MY BREED. I need structured daily exercise and further discipline/ socialization training, but I'm eager to please (w/ treats) and quick to learn. I am a DIAMOND in the RUFF & will give you back 200% if you will work with me to put the demons of my puppy past behind. Please give me a chance today!!! My time is running out!!

For more info/application - pls email: INFO@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG

animal.description:
12/20/20 Welcome to STAF, beautiful girl! A big-hearted rescuer found Noelle in a county shelter, in sad shape. She nursed her back to health, then entrusted her to STAF to find her forever home. Noelle is just around 1 1/2 years old (est. birthdate 6/19) and shy of 60 pounds. She is as friendly and sweet as she is horrible on leash ... our volunteers are soaking up the former while working on the latter :O) A basic manners class will go a long way with this cutie. Please check back for updates as we get to know Noelle better. Visit www.STAF.org for more information on our adoption process.

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

Please visit www.STAF.org for visiting hours, a downloadable application, and additional information.

animal.description:
Please share this girl for us. ?? 

If there is any dog that needs a home, it’s Oreo. Oreo has been in a shelter system for 2 years now. She hasn’t found the right home. I know our Slumdog family can help this girl. We have had several flighty cases who have found great homes. 

Oreo is a 3 year old, very petite and polite pitty mix. She is a fearful girl but she thrives being around other animals. She would make a great addition to a “pack”. Oreo is good with all sizes of dogs, ranging from 9lbs to 75lbs (my variety), good with cats and Tunie, the pig. She was excellent for her bath and nail trim. She is an extreme flight risk and I can’t stress this enough. She will need a secure, PRIVACY fenced in yard. She will also need to be leash walked in the yard. If there’s a way to escape, she will find it. We are already working on recall and she follows you around if she trusts you. This is a case where Oreo will pick her person. She’s cuddled up to me on the couch right now and has been stuck like glue to my side. But I already have a pack and she deserves her forever home... 

Oreo is not a dog park or pet store kind of dog. She’s a good, solid neighborhood walk to get her exercise in but other than that, she would be safest at home. She does get car sick as well so that just adds to the list of reasons why she shouldn’t be a traveling dog. She just does not have the confidence. 

I didn’t know Oreo when she came into the shelter but I believe that 2 years in a shelter can change a dog. If there is a special person out there that is willing to give Oreo the attention and dedication she needs, I truly believe she would flourish in the right home. Please share. She has already been spayed, vaccinated and is heartworm negative. ??

To apply to meet Oreo, please complete an application and a volunteer will be in touch. https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/13467/generic

animal.description:
Penny
7 year old female Jack Russell Terrier/Border Collie mix

Penny is a mature lass who knows just what she wants in life.  Being a little bit older and out of the puppy stage she has bursts of energy but does tend to take her time and lounge around in comfy spots whenever possible.  She can be a bit cranky from time to time so we are looking for a home with no children and no other pets so she can enjoy her space and enjoy that extra attention as an only dog.  Her dream home would be full of people to shower her with attention and cuddle with her.  She would also love a home that enjoys to get out on walks regularly.  Once she is settled into her home and family and when this pesky covid isn’t a problem she is very friendly and loves when company comes around to give her extra attention.  Penny does guard her food from people and other animals so would also like a family who has some experience dealing with resource guarding and is comfortable continuing with training to help her overcome her anxieties and protectiveness around those high value items.
Penny has been vaccinated, spayed, microchipped, dewormed, heartworm tested and treated with Advantage. 
She came to us as an unclaimed stray from LACC. 

The adoption fee is $600 and includes spay/neuter (dogs over 6 months), vaccines, heartworm test (dogs over 6 months), deworming, Flea and tick prevention and microchip. Please visit www.paws-united.com to fill out an application.
**For puppies under 6 months a $200 spay/neuter rebate will be given with proof of spay/neuter certificate signed by a vet, if they have not been done prior to adoption.**
**Please note we DO NOT adopt our dogs as outdoor/farm dogs. These dogs are coming to us as stray, roaming or dogs that have lived a life tied to a chain. Our goal is to bring them in the house off the chain and give them a pampered indoor dogs lifestyle. Unless otherwise stated we will not even consider a home that has intentions of leaving our dogs outdoors or tied to a chain**

animal.description:
1/23/2021

Holly was found wandering around on her own in AL.  A kind family took her in and began rehabilitating her.  She weighed just 35 lbs at that time and was in very sad shape.  While in their home, Holly was doted upon by the family and their young children. 

Holly is a beautiful purebred Golden Retriever estimated to be 8 years old.  She is truly lovely inside and out, happy and always sweet.  She is great with all people, even the little ones.  Holly is low activity, fine with leash walking, and riding in a car.  She was timid when first meeting a new dog while with the family who first took her in, but has been fine with other dogs at the vet clinic.  Cats are an unknown.  Holly enjoys stuffed animals, as you can see in her pictures.  Like most Goldens, she lives for love and attention and being with her humans.

When Holly was examined by our vet, it was discovered that she has a degenerative spinal condition and allergies.  With the help of anti-inflammatory medicine and supplements, Holly is currently much more comfortable and enjoys playing and carrying around her beloved stuffies.  She will always need her medicine to help maintain her mobility.  Her allergies are under control with a dog food that works for her, a diet which must continue when in her adoptive home.  Because her medicine and diet are an absolute requirement for Holly, we consider her to be a ‘special needs’ dog.  We are hopeful that Holly will maintain her current mobility for a few years, although it is possible that her spinal condition will slow her down more quickly.  It is heartbreaking that she has this degenerative condition but she does not feel sorry for herself and enjoys every single day.  She is looking for a family who will accept her special needs and open their hearts to her.  She deserves so much to be spoiled and loved for her retirement years, however long that may be.

Holly is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, heartworm negative, and ready to be part of a loving home.  If you have a big heart for older Goldens and would like to be part of Holly’s rescue story, please contact  Lisa at lkh5@mchsi.com to be considered to adopt Holly.  If not yet approved, please fill out an application on the Adoption Info page.  

Rescued dogs come with a range of needs - from behavioral to emotional to medical.  When approved applicants adopt such dogs, they agree to continue the rehabilitation we have begun.    

If not yet approved, please use this link to submit an online application:  http://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/8O06oK9Af8

You can also visit our website to learn more:  http://jlgoldenretrieverrescue.com/index.html

Please DO NOT use the ASK ABOUT button to contact us, about this dog, as that will delay our ability to respond to your inquiry.  

Please direct any questions regarding your application status to Lisa at:   LKH5@MCHSI.COM

Thank you!
 
About Our Rescue 
Before being approved to adopt, all potential adopters will be required to complete our online application and participate in our pre-adoption review process. The process includes the completion of an online application, a reference from the applicants' vet, a phone interview, and a visit to the applicants' home.  The application process helps us determine what type of Golden would be best suited for the applicants' life style.  In some cases, the specific dog you are interested in may have found a home before this process is complete or further assessment may indicate that this dog is not the right match for your family.  We are frequently getting new Goldens in need of a home, so we encourage you to apply and complete the application process so that when the right dog comes along you will be ready. 

Adoption Fees:
$700  Purebred puppy to 12 months                                 
$400  Dogs under 7 years
$200  Senior, 7+ years
$500  Bonded pair

The information provided on each dog is based on the observations of our vets, volunteers, fosters, and when available, trainers. While we do our best to report any and all issues, J & L does not make any guarantees as to the health or temperament of any dog. Dogs evolve differently in different environments and we cannot predict with any certainty how the dog you adopt will behave and adapt in your home.

A contract is signed on the day of adoption.  Under the terms of the contract, all adopters are required to bring their dog to a vet within 7 business days.  All dogs receive basic veterinary care prior to adoption.  However, if an adopter's vet identifies an illness that an adopter is not willing to treat, then the dog may be returned and a full refund would be provided. 

Most of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  We do not have a facility to visit.  We are committed to our dogs before, during, and after adoption! To this end, the rescue retains an interest in each dog and our dogs can never be surrendered, re-homed, or sold. Should an adopter no longer be able to keep their J & L dog, J & L must be notified so that we can take the dog back into rescue and place it into another home. We reserve the right to remove a dog at any time should we find the adopter is no longer providing proper care.  Adopters agree to follow up visits as needed.  

Please be a ray of light for this J & L dog and make a tax deductible donation toward medical care and other expenses.   Every cent of your generosity goes directly toward the care of a J & L dog.

THANK YOU!

animal.description:
JC
3 year old male Jack Russell Terrier/German Shepherd

JC is a very sweet, loving and fun little ball of energy.  Like all JR's he'll play fetch as long as your arm works and will do best with a combination of mental and physical stimulation day to day. JC is also a great fan of tug of war.  He does love to burrow under blankets and loves to cuddle on the couch.  JC really brings the Scooby doo personality to every day.  He absolutely is a toy junkie but needs tough toys as he is a little ruff when playing with them.  He does know to do his chewing on bones and toys and has not tried to chew on other things.  JC came in needing a lot of work on his leash but with proper guidance he is getting better at walking without pulling and he's starting to realize that when you stop, he needs to as well.  With the help of treat motivation he's been mastering turning around and looking at his foster home when he's not able to continue moving.  Always the energetic buddy, when he goes into the back yard, he bolts out like a bullet and runs to make sure there are no squirrels in the back yard.  His foster home reports him to be keeping her laughing and smiling every day with his personality and unique look.
JC would love a home where he can be an only dog as he is protective of resources with other dogs.  A home where there are no cats or other small critters as he does have some prey drive and we are looking for homes with only older children (10+).  A family who likes adventure and enjoys training and teaching a dog will make his heart sore.  He is highly food motivated and loves to learn new things.
*Special consideration.  Before entering rescue while still in the shelter, JC was being given sedation for his neuter and reacted when the needle poked him.  He did bite the vet during this moment which resulted in some broken skin.  Because of this JC does have a muzzle order in the city of London.  This means if he finds his furever family in London when out and about off his property he will have to be muzzled.  JC has shown no signs of aggression day to day in his foster home.  We would recommend a muzzle for vetting procedures moving forward as well.   
JC has been vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested, neutered, microchipped and treated with Advantage. 
He came to us as an unclaimed stray from LACC. 

The adoption fee is $600 and includes spay/neuter (dogs over 6 months), vaccines, heartworm test (dogs over 6 months), deworming, Flea and tick prevention and microchip. Please visit www.paws-united.com to fill out an application.
**For puppies under 6 months a $200 spay/neuter rebate will be given with proof of spay/neuter certificate signed by a vet, if they have not been done prior to adoption.**
**Please note we DO NOT adopt our dogs as outdoor/farm dogs. These dogs are coming to us as stray, roaming or dogs that have lived a life tied to a chain. Our goal is to bring them in the house off the chain and give them a pampered indoor dogs lifestyle. Unless otherwise stated we will not even consider a home that has intentions of leaving our dogs outdoors or tied to a chain**

animal.description:
**If you're interested in learning more about Chloe, please email adhakcount@gmail.com**

Full of energy and adorable personality, Chloe is a wonderful companion... perfect both on rambling outdoor adventures and for quiet evening cuddles on the couch. Curious, super smart, and playful in the extreme, she's a great fit for outdoorsy, experienced dog owners looking for a new sidekick. Prone to getting the Zoomies out in the yard, she loves to prance around and keep you laughing. Chloe is just a bouncing bundle of cute! 

 

She's gentle and friendly, is quick to warm up to just about any human,. She's a quick learner and responds very well to positive reinforcement. At the same, time, she's quite confident and independent. When she's indoors, she's usually quiet and relaxed. She does tend to bark at noises outside, so may not be suited to apartment living. At walk time, she waits patiently by the front door for you to put on her halter and leash, and after she's home she curls up happily by your feet when you're reading in your favorite armchair. She's great in car rides and loves two long walks (and many romps in the yard) each day. Once she's spent both playtime and quiet time with you, she'll become your best buddy forever!

 

When meeting new dogs on walks around the neighborhood, however, Chloe's so enthusiastic that she can go a bit overboard! This degree of enthusiasm makes her a good match for experienced dog owners who are ready to work with her on some "refresher training work. While Chloe knows some basic verbal cues (like "sit and "come) she'll need a patient friend to help her learn the finer points of dog etiquette!

 

She will be happiest in a single-family home with a yard, and may do best with either an individual, a couple or a small family with older children. She's prone to rowdy, energetic play which makes her a poor fit for a home with an older dog, or one with cats or small children.

 

Chloe is a real gem - loving, funny, gentle and loyal - like a pearl in the rough. She's just waiting to find her forever friend who will help polish up her rough edges, allowing her brilliant luster to shine!

animal.description:
Hi ! ?

My name is Freddy. I am a 3 month ish mix puppy from Mississippi. The vet thinks we are cattle/heeler mixes. 

 I am a very high energy breed but also very cuddly.  I love to play and sunbathe. 

* 1/31 update: Freddy is making lots of progress with working on sharing food. Over the past two weeks he slowly worked up to eating around dogs, sharing toys and water. When we met Freddy two weeks ago he struggled with sharing food with dogs/puppies (attacked if another dog or puppy came near when he is eating or drinking) this was due to his past as a stray, fighting for food. In combination with how this puppy was “negatively nurtured”(past negative experiences) this puppy’s “nature” (high energy/high arousal breeds) play a role in the intense behavior. 

We are looking for people with another dog and the dedication to help Freddy continue to work on his behavior.  

Freddy did NOT struggle with any human aggressive in any way, and only had issues with sharing with other puppies/dogs. His issues are almost gone but we want to make sure he is continuously worked and managed to make sure he never has issues in the future with sharing with dogs. 
. 

All puppies are spayed / neutered , microchipped, vaccinated (rabies, distemper, parvo, boardatella), have 2 recent negative fecals, 2 recent health exams, and have been on monthly heart guard and flea and tick medicine . 

To apply to adopt https://www.secondchanceranchrescue.com/apply-to-adopt

animal.description:
*Please read the full bio*
If you are interested in meeting Moxie, we require an approved application. If you have questions regarding adoption, please visit our website --> www.adoptionfirstanimalrescueky.com
Please do not email us asking if the dog is available, if she is on pet finder she is. We will not respond to emails that can be answered on our website.
Moxie is an 8-year-old poodle mix, weighing in at 9 pounds. Moxie is a very sweet girl and is great with kids older than 6. She is definitely a lap dog and enjoys all the attention that she can get. Moxie is very quiet, only barking/talking when she wants some love and attention. She is working on house training, she uses the pee pad or outside for all urine, but still poops in the house. This little girl is just too cold to go out in this winter weather, she seems more concerned with getting back inside the house than doing her business outside. She did have an extensive surgery when she was spayed, we sent the mass off, and it was benign.

Complete Application
You must complete the adoption application in full to be considered for adoption. 
Home Check
All adoptions do require a home check. If you are not comfortable with a home check please do not apply. We want to ensure the safety of our dogs and to make sure the adoptive family is comfortable. 
Meet and Greet
If your application has been approved we will schedule a meet and greet for the dog of your choice or for a few we think might be a good fit for your family. 
Sign Adoption Contract
This must be read and signed prior to adoption.
Adoption Fee 
Once everything has been reviewed the adoption fee will need to be paid. Puppies under 6 months is $300, over 6 months is $250, over 10 years is $150. Adoption fee includes: -Spay or Neuter -Microchip (additional registration fee required to transfer ownership to adopters) -Up to date on vaccinations -All animals have been examined by a veterinarian ** All adoption fees are non refundable.

animal.description:
Breed:Pit Bull/Shar-Pei MixAge: About 3 yrs oldSex: Female (fixed)Size: Large (55 lbs)Color: Champagne & White
MEET ANGEL PIE!!!!
There aren't enough words to describe how wonderful Angel Pie is! She is one of the sweetest, best behaved, and most loving dogs her foster family has ever had. She is so laid back and easy going that she instantly blended in with her foster family as if she had always been there.
When Angel Pie found her way to the shelter, she was very emaciated. In addition, she had developed a bad case of mastitis from having her puppies taken away too soon. As if that wasn't enough, she was also positive for tick born diseases and heartworms. Angel Pie has been treated for all of her ailments and is now ready to find her forever home.
When Angel Pie first went into foster care, she was very sad. It was obvious that she missed her puppies. Her foster sisters helped to bring Angel Pie out of her depression so that her sweet and playful personality could come out. Angel Pie gets a little separation anxiety. She won't do anything bad - she just gets mopey and sad. For that reason, she should go to a home with at least one other dog.
Angel Pie likes to follow her foster people around the house. But if they aren't doing anything interesting, she will go and find a sunbeam to lie in. And when her foster people come home, she greets them with a full body wiggle!
Angel Pie's energy level is medium to low. She is perfectly content being a couch potato. However, she also likes to join in on any activities that are going on. She likes to "go with the flow." Angel Pie does get nippy when she gets overly excited, but she is sensitive and responds very well when told "no." This behavior is getting better as she learns the difference between playing with people and playing with other dogs.
Angel Pie walks easily on a leash. She comes to her name (which she chose for herself), and is starting to learn her commands. She is not food motivated, but she is eager to please and loves to be loved on.
Angel Pie is ready to start the next chapter of her life as your new best friend!
Angel Pie is microchipped and crate trained. She is up-to-date and her adoption fee is $350.

animal.description:
Hi, my SOLR name is Kira, but my foster mama calls me Moira Rose, and I love it and respond to it. It suits me perfectly. I am a little over a year old, weigh in at 40 lbs, and I am a precious little lady.

I LOVE my foster mama. I am very comfortable around her and she is the one I trust completely. However, I am quite shy around new people (especially men and children). I'll keep my distance, and will approach on my own, but still am not sure I can trust them. Sometimes if they move too fast, I'll bark at them. I'm not trying to be mean; I'm just reacting in fear. My foster mama wishes everyone can see how cuddly and adorable I am with her. She can move quickly around me, roughhouse, snuggle, kiss my face, rub all over, take toys and food away, and all the things she does with my fur brothers and sister. We both know I am a very smart little girl and have the sweetest disposition, I just need to find someone who will be patient with me until I can connect like I do with my foster mama.

I learned how to use the doggie door, navigate stairs, go into my kennel (which I love), and find my place bed. I take treats gently and eat my food like a lady. I'm currently on medicine for Valley Fever (I have a mild case), and take my pill gently when it's wrapped in ham. I LOVE to chase my fur siblings around the yard and chew on Nylabones. I must have Nylabones. I have completed a basic obedience class, but would love more training to help build my confidence.

For the most part, I have freedom to roam around the house and can be trusted. But, because I am still a young dog learning how to live my best life, my mama knows where I am all the time so I don't chew on things I shouldn't.

During the day I mostly sleep like the other dogs. I love our playtime in the yard and Zoomies are my favorite. I love to play Follow the Leader and romp around with my fur siblings. I do like to chase the kitties in the house, but respond to correction when I'm told to leave the kitties alone. I would never hurt them, I just want to chase and play with them. If my humans leave, they kennel me just like the other dogs. We all just chill out and take an extra snooze. I am quiet in my kennel. I used to sleep in my kennel at night, but I have found sleeping cuddled up with my mama or the other dogs is more my style.

I would love to have a fur-sibling to play with in my fur-ever home, but I think I'd be feel most comfortable in a home with no children. I'm a sweet little girl who has a lot of love to offer. I do need someone who is patient and gives me time to feel safe. I promise the wait will be worth it. 2/2/21 2:49 PM
animal.name: Kira

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in adoption from Palmetto Paws. If you would like to be considered to adopt from PPAR please complete the online application on the home page. Completing an application does not guarantee an adoption. The age to be considered for adoption is 21.

We will not consider applications for those not able to meet/adopt on the next upcoming Saturday or at a time designated by the rescue. Adoptions are done usually on Saturdays as we are all volunteers who work full time during the week. Dogs live in private foster homes. We do not host events and there is no opportunity to view multiple dogs. 
We will not consider incomplete applications. We will not process applications that are not for a specific dog listed on petfinder. We do not process and "hold" applications. We do not ship dogs and we do not arrange transports. All adopters must be present to complete the adoption. If an adopter is approved we do a “meet and greet” with a specific dog or pup. If at the meet we all agree it’s a good match, then the adoption takes place at that time. Their is no opportunity to meet and adopt at a later date. Again, please only apply if you are available on Saturday and ready to adopt.

Please keep in mind that we do our best to make an educated guess as to the breeds of our rescued pets. In rescue we rarely see the parents puppies, and even when we do, they are usually mixed breeds as well. We will never promise a particular breed or adult size.

We do our best to put all info we have in the bio. We will not respond to inquires regarding information that is already detailed in the bio. 

 My name is Abbey. I am about one year old and I weigh around 35 pounds. Adoptable pets are spayed/neutered (unless the rescue Veterinarian deems the pup/dog will need to be adopted on a SN contract), have age appropriate vaccines, are current on hw and flea preventatives and microchipped. 

Abbey is currently in a foster home. Is is crate trained and they are working on housetraining. She is walked many times a day and has yet to meet a stranger. She is very energetic and sweet.

All adopters are provided with a medical summary, a new collar and leash, an opportunity to go over basic training/pet care and help shopping for supplies if needed. 

 The adoption fee is $395.

If interested in adoption please submit an application! The application is found on our home page at palmettopaws.petfinder.com

animal.description:
Jaxx is a really great dog.  We're not sure of his breed, so guess is spaniel and pekingese or similar.  He's a young dog, maybe a few years old and weighs in about 25 pounds.  He's small, but sturdy.

Jaxx is a local dog, that was surrendered to his local animal services and in turn, transferred into our care.  He was surrendered as he bit a child.  There was no hospital visit and no stitches needed, but he does have that bite history and he can be a bit set in his ways, so a home without kids 15 and under, is best for Jaxx.

Jaxx loves being with people, and can be a bit velcro, so a home with someone that works from home often or can take their dog to work is best.  We can see him having some separation anxiety if it's not worked on during the pandemic.

Jaxx, we're sure has pekingese in him, and that requires an experienced handler.  He's not suited to first time dog owners.   Though he's super smart, that intelligence is offset by an independent mind and a wide stubborn streak. 

Training Jaxx is possible, but it'll be a challenge for sure. Jaxx considers himself in charge of all situations, so training needs to happen with an element of Jaxx still being in charge, but not realizing you actually are.  

His adopter will need to work with a professional trainer to help Jaxx be the best version of himself.  He has so much incredible potential, and just needs someone to get him over the finish line of best behaviour.

His breed does not handle  discipline and it can cause him to become defensive and possibly to bite, which is where his bite may have originated from.  He will never want to be forced to do something he doesn't want to do.

The difficulties aside, Jaxx is a really sweet boy.  Loves to love.  Is great on car rides.  Wants to be with his people always and in the hands of an experienced handler, will quickly become someones best buddy to have amazing adventures with.

FROM HIS FOSTER DAD:

Jaxx is an affectionate little guy who is happiest on your lap or, when he needs a break, lying down right beside you. 

He was a little nervous with us at first but didn't take long at all to relax and make himself comfortable.

Jaxx is great in an apartment or condo. He never barks indoors and is happy to lounge around the house - so long as he has a human nearby. He gets a little anxious when left alone at night but usually settles down quickly enough. He loves his walks, and will hop up from wherever he's resting as soon as he hears the word "walk".

Jaxx is very straightforward to walk as well. He insists on walking on your right side, and will run around you to make sure this happens. He also tends to dart back and forth a bit, so may need some extra attention to avoid crossing paths with other people or getting onto the road. However he is not stubborn with the lead.

He is very well housetrained - no accidents so far in foster care. 

He is cautious but calm with other dogs but does occasionally bark, especially if he can't get close enough to say hi.

There are a couple of minor cases where Jaxx has growled at us. When you take off his harness he'll try to grab onto it, and if he does get it will not easily let you take it back. He also doesn't like to be shifted around too much when lying down (although picking him up to put him on your lap is fine). He's very easily distracted though, so if he does get a little grumpy, it doesn't last long.

Jaxx has been our easiest dog to feed so far. Put any amount of dry food in front of him and he will quickly eat it. sThe only risk is overfeeding!

All in all, Jaxx is a beautiful and affectionate dog that will fit right in with anyone willing to give him lots of attention.

____________________________________________

As of today, though our protocols could change tomorrow, we are still moving forward with adoptions. Our process has changed from some of the previous elements: We are a registered animal welfare organization, so we are deemed an essential service.

All paperwork completed online, video home visits, meet and greets outside respecting social distancing, leashes/collars/supplies wiped down and disinfected (GermiCide 3 wipes), disinfectant on the dog prior to handoff (Aqueos wipes for dogs)

-----------------------

To note: the above description is relevant to this dog in his current setting. Home changes & adopter personalities can bring out different behaviours not previously seen.

We do not specifically kid/cat test our dogs when they arrive at Mattie's Place. That just wouldn't be fair to the dog or child/cat.

We also do not claim, endorse, suggest or hint at, that any of our dogs are hypoallergenic, low shed or no-shed.

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, deworming, defleaing, vaccinations, nose to tail health exam, leash|collar, 6 months of preventative based on season/need, DNA test for entertainment purposes, dishes, poop bags, food and any extras she has accumulated in foster care.

Please note, RAGOM's adoption territory includes Minnesota, Iowa, North and South Dakota, and western Wisconsin within 75 miles of the MN border.   At this time, we do not adopt out of our territory.  

Lady was surrendered to RAGOM by a Good Samaritan. She is a young Golden Retriever who is blind. She was born with undeveloped eyes so has never known sight. Lady does well figuring out her surroundings but requires a special family who will be able to adjust to her needs as a blind dog. Lady requires another playful dog who is about the same size in her adoptive home . She should have either a physical fence or be taken out on a leash—no tie outs. 

Lady is good with the children in the foster home but she does like to play rough so it would be best if her forever home had older kids (8+) who were more confident with her rough play. 

To learn more about Lady, see her bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/lady-20-162

Placement Requirements:
Good With Dogs: Yes-Required
Good With Cats: Not Tested
Good With Kids: 8+
Fence: Physical Fence Optional
Age: 1

If you are interested in any of the dogs available at Retrieve a Golden of the Midwest (RAGOM), you can read our adoption process and apply to adopt, which can be found at https://ragom.org/our-adoption-process. 

RAGOM’s adoption territory includes: Minnesota; Iowa; North Dakota; South Dakota; Western Wisconsin (within 75 miles of the Minnesota border)

animal.description:
Hey there! I’m Chief! I am a super sweet, young Lab Mix; emphasis on the MIX!! I was found as a stray and no one came looking for me so I became an ARF dog! 

I am approximately 1-2 years old and I weigh 50 lbs. I may not be all the way done growing so it’s possible I could be close to 60 Lbs. once I’m fully-grown. I am friendly, sweet and spunky! I have lots of energy and love to give to one very lucky family. I get along GREAT with other dogs and I love every single human I come in contact with. I will need a large, fenced yard to run and play as I please; I would not be suitable for an apartment. I love to go on walks and run around with my friends; I will make the most wonderful family pet. I would love a home with another dog or two to play with; I am the friendliest, happiest guy on the planet and I enjoy running around with my best friends and playing with toys.

The fee to adopt Chief is $200.00; this includes spay/neuter, deworming, vaccinations and a microchip. If you are interested in adopting Chief, please visit our website. www.arfhouse.org and fill out an adoption application. 

**Please Note: Chief is currently located at our facility in Sherman, Texas. Adoptions are by-appointment only; if you would like to meet Chief, please fill out an application on our website. Once we have your application, our Adoption Coordinator will follow up with you ASAP with any questions she may have, or to set up a meet-and-greet.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Frosty! I was rescued in Georgia along with my sister, prior to arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am a very energetic pup, but no matter what I'm doing I will always sit and give you a great big smile, when you ask me to! Prior to arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue I was living in a foster home with LOTS of other dogs. I'd love to find a home with a great big yard for me to run around and play whenever I wanted to. I get along well with others, but can sometimes be selective with who I choose to engage with. I do appear to have a prey drive and would do best in a home without any feline companions. I could definitely benefit from some further training, including potty training, but I know that I'll get the hang of everything very fast. My favorite place to be is right by your side, no matter what it is that you're doing. I think I'd be happiest in an adult home or a home with older children. I love to play with toys and balls and can keep myself entertained quite well. But my absolute favorite thing to do is give hugs and kisses to anyone and everyone who comes by!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Andres! I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I'm a sweet boy who loves to cuddle and play, but I can be a little bit skittish and shy when I first meet new people, dogs, or find myself in new situations. I think I would make an excellent family dog, and I even think that I'd be able to live happily in a home with a feline companion. I'd be a solid pick for any first-time adopter, but I would love it if I could find a new owner who could help me learn how to work through my shyness. I'm small and don't take up much space so I would make the perfect apartment dog! A quiet lifestyle is definitely the lifestyle for me and cuddling up on the couch next to you would make me the happiest pup in the whole world! I don't think I'd like to go out and about with you in public but I would love to be a permanent fixture in your living room. I do appear to be well-trained and while I'm not totally potty-trained yet, I do keep my kennel very neat!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Rosie! I was rescued, along with my 6 puppies, from an Alabama animal shelter before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am a super sweet girl and I absolutely love human attention - so much that when you stop petting me, I will whine and let you know that I'd like you to keep going! I like to play with dogs, but I can be selective sometimes with who I choose to engage with. Sometimes, when in social situations with other dogs, I can be a little bit skittish and very cautious, so formal introductions when meeting new friends are helpful! I think that I could make an excellent family pet, but would prefer to be with children over the age of 12 who are better able to respect my boundaries. I could be a good pick for either an experienced dog owner or a first-time adopter, but I need a confident owner who is going to be ablet to reassure me that everything is ok to help me get over my nervousness. I think I could be happy in any type of home, either an apartment or a house with a big yard, but I think that I would definitely do best in a quieter home. I could use some additional training, particularly with leash walking, but once I get the hang of it, I think that I could be a good dog for you to take out and about in public if you wanted to. I do appear to be potty-trained here at the ranch and I am confident that I can learn anything you want me to, as long as you're willing to work with me while I warm up to new things and new people.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Daisy! I was rescued from South Carolina, along with my sister, before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. A Good Samaritan helped get us out of a bad situation where we were living outside, prior to our arrival. I have a very sweet personality and tend to be very playful, particularly with my sister. Between my sister and I, I would say that I'm the more submissive pup in the pair.I like to play with other dogs, regardless of their size, but can sometimes be a little bit selective too. I think I would make an excellent family pet, even in a home with small children. I even think that I could live harmoniously with a feline companion. Either an experienced dog owner or a first-time adopter would be happy to have me join their family, and I think that I could make myself comfortable in any variety of home situations, from an apartment to a great big farm. A busy or quiet lifestyle would suit me just fine and I love to welcome new visitors so if you like to entertain, I'm the perfect pup for you! I may even be the type of pup that you want to bring out and about with you in public. I could probably use some additional training, but I am very neat in my kennel here at the ranch. I also love to go for long-leashed walks and running around and playing with toys.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Mary! I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I'm a young puppy with lots of energy and spunk! I love to run around and play! I'm friendly and happy and just want to get to know you. Sometimes I can be a little bit shy and skittish in new situations with new people but I usually adjust quickly. My favorite activity here on the ranch is definitely getting to chase after a tennis ball. Aside from having tons of energy, sometimes I can be loud, as I don't know how to control my barking yet. You have to remember, I'm a lot like a baby and have not necessarily adapted to a schedule yet so you may find that I'm staying up in my crate at night, and sleeping during the day. I need lots of direction and training, and that doesn't just mean puppy pre-school classes. I need you to show me the right and wrong things to do. Please don't be mad if in the process I wind up chewing some of your belongings or if I have accidents in the house - I promise I will get the hang of things! I require LOTS of time, energy, and patience, but my sweet little face makes it all worth it! This is a learning curve for us both but I promise that if you put the time and energy into helping me grow big and strong, you'll wind up with a wonderful little best friend for life.

Shorty was an owner surrender he is at least 10 and has never been on a leash. He lived with a male senior citizen so he is use to a quiet house he also is vey quiet. When you first get home he dances for attention on his rear legs whines a little out of excitement and that’s about it. He likes to sleep in blankets so he can snuggle in and cover up. His favorite place to be is on the couch. 

Hey, I’m Shorty, May I be your new best friend.  I’m about 10 years old and weight just 6 pounds.

MISSYS HAVEN CANINE Rescue, in San Antonio TX, does not have a shelter - ALL of our dogs are raised in foster homes in the San Antonio area. Each dog comes spayed or neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations that are appropriate for their age, microchipped, heartworm tested and on current on monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventative. 

ALL OF THIS IS INCLUDED IN THE ADOPTION FEE OF $200.00 FOR LOCAL DOGS AND $250.00 FOR PUPPIES. ( Local is in the state of Texas)! Medical records will come with each dog at the time of adoption.

IF THIS IS AN OUT OF STATE ADOPTION, TRANSPORT TO YOU is included in the adoption fee of $400.00 for adult dogs and $500.00 for puppies. We transport all over the country!!

All our dogs are socialized and we try to provide you a good understanding of the dog’s personality. Please visit our website for more information about what we do; http://www.missyshavencr.org.  You will also find helpful our adoption application and pictures of our all our dogs/pups looking for homes!!

Don’t forget to like us at http://Facebook.com/missyshavencr

animal.description: Meet the Espresso Pups! This litter of adorable possibly Labrador and Spaniel mixes is guaranteed to brighten your day! Now that these cuties are around 2 months old, they are ready for their forever families. Is that you? Their mama, Espresso is a super sweet girl, who weighs about 40 lbs. animal.description: Maui is an adorable 2 year old pittie who had a very difficult early life. After suffering abuse and neglect (including burns), he and a companion dog were rescued by a good samaritan. In those few weeks, Maui has shown what a loving and dedicated dog he is, and he is enjoying being treated properly, the way he deserves. Maui is housebroken and roams free in the house. He walks nicely on leash. It's unknown how he is with cats, but he gets along well with the dog he was with, possibly some food guarding with the other dog due to not being fed propertly. Maui however has developed separation anxiety. It's heartbreaking, as you can almost see how desperate he is not to be alone. Maui's caregiver is afraid he will destroy a regular crate and afraid to leave him alone since he rents. He has been missing work to care for Maui and is struggling financially due to loss of work. Maui urgently needs placement that can help him overcome or manage his separation anxiety. Please contact Outreach@sjras.org to help Maui.

animal.description:
Duke is a 9-10 week old Mutt. We honestly have no idea what breeds Duke's is, but we do know that he came from the streets of Texas and both parents, and both parents parents were mutts, so Duke probably has 5-15 breeds in him. We are guessing Duke and his siblings will be around 50-60lbs when full grown, but again, that is just a guess.

Duke and his siblings were found living in a barn/abandoned shack in Texas with a pack of dogs who had been running the streets for some time. We were able to catch all the puppies whent hey were about 7.5 weeks old. Since they had not had any human contact until we were able to catch them, they were very weary of humans before getting to their foster homes here in CO. They were all split into separate foster homes where they have been really well socialized for the last 2 weeks. They are still a little nervous and will need patient humans, but they have to love human affection, play time, other dogs in the foster home, and to follow their fosters around the home. They are soooo sweet and really want nothing more than to be loved. These pups are also incredibly smart! They are learning really quickly and listen really well!

We are going to require Duke and his 8 other siblings go to families with other dogs so they can continue to learn from other K9's to be wonderful companions. 

If you are interested in adopting Duke or one of his siblings, please fill out our adoption application at brighterdaysdogrescue.com

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO BEFORE SUBMITTING AN APPLCIATION OR INQUIRY.

Meet April!

April is a very special girl who needs a very special home! She came to us through the local open-intake animal shelter where she was brought in as part of a cruelty case with her two babies. They separated her from her babies and the first two weeks she was sitting in the shelter she went crazy, it was heartbreaking to see. After her babies got adopted, an amazing shelter worker really took April under her wing and started bringing her outside and teaching her tricks. April always did amazing in playgroups and loved all the humans that worked there. When we saw April's grin and heard her sad story, we were gonners and she joined the Mafia!

We're hoping to find April a very special home that will help her forget her sad past. If you are looking for a forever couch sidekick and hiking buddy, April is your lady. If you are hoping to take your dog with you everywhere-- bars, Lowes, pet stores-- she is probably NOT the dog for you. You see, given that she was a part of a cruelty case, she finds strangers to be very scary. BUT if her foster mama introduces her to a new human, and they have yummy snacks, she'll forget they're a stranger in about 10 minutes. She WANTS to trust, and love and be loved. She's just a tad skeptical.

She can be reactive on leash with strangers, so a fenced yard to get her energy out or a quieter home with not too much foot traffic is ideal for her. When leashed, she will pull towards strangers and bark, but she is controllable with a harness. 

She is in a foster home with dogs of all ages and sizes and gets along great with all of them. She loves car rides and is totally house broken. She is not a huge fan of her crate and would love her family to be around more often than not.

April is about 3 years old and 47 lbs, so she has a ton of life and energy, but she's over her anoying puppy phase. All of our dogs are spay/neutered and up to date on age appropriate vaccinations April is currently in a MA-area foster home and is available for meet and greets with approved adopters, so please use the webaddress below to apply. 

Ps, if you can see my profile, I am still available for adoption. Please follow this link to submit an application: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/13170/generic

One in three pets becomes lost at some point in their life. We have partnered with Fi Collars (tryfi.com) to provide our pups and adopters with an extra layer of safety. If chosen to adopt, you will be given the option to add $100 to the adoption fee to recieve a Fi collar and 1 year subscription ($250 value).

Please make sure your vet, references, and landlord, as applicable, are expecting to be contacted by a Mutt Mafia representative. This helps expidite the process. 

Note: Due to increased demand, we will NOT be responding to all inquiries. If you have an issue with the application, feel free to send us an email. If you have questions about the adoption process, most should be answered by the information within the application.

animal.description: Jolie is a sweet, senior girl that is regal like a princess but is low-key and laid back. She is not demanding at all and enjoys going for walks and just chilling out. She will be great company for someone wanting a companion that is calm, housetrained and really no trouble at all. She enjoys being brushed is good with a bath. Jolie is a Maremma Sheepdog mix and spent her early years or a large farm, working, guarding her flock. She has been a pet in recent years and loves nothing more than just hanging out with her people/person, inside or outside, going for walks and riding in the car. She really wants a family/person that will take her for walks and let her be inside with them. Jolie has lived happily, with a medium size dog and enjoys the company of other dogs once she gets to know them. We do not know how she is with cats. She has done well with kids that she has been around. Her calm demeanor will make her a great addition to most any family. Jolie is 10 years old and weighs about 70 pounds. She would love to have a new family to spend her senior years with.You can apply on line at www.hsvawl.org by completing the Adoption Application on the home page.

animal.description:
Bingo now goes by the name of Toby.. He has been adopted and returned 2x. He is potty trained but is a flight risk at first. He needs a home with a secure fenced in yard and another dog to play with. He needs a patient home that is willing to give him plenty of time to come out of his shell. He prefers women and has also done well with children. He can become territorial and will bark at and nip men once he gets comfortable in his new home.

After being adopted for almost a year, his owner has decided that it is best to rehome him. His progress was slow and he wasn't able to turn into the life companion that his owner needed. We are looking for a home with another dog to help teach him to trust his human family members and a secure fenced in yard to help prevent him from running away. He will be a flight risk until he learns where his family and food are.

 

Razzle, Dazzle, Bingo, Nixon & Remy came to us from Warren County Humane Society. The Humane Society intervened in a hoarding case with 148 poodles in September of 2019. The community and rescue support was huge at first and allowed them to move all but about 30 of the poodles, all of which had the most severe socialization or medical issues. Stray Haven went in, when they were at this point and selected 5 of these babies to help share the load of moving them into their new forever.

 

Bingo is probably the youngest of the poodles we took in, but is also the most vocal. When in doubt he will bark. We can see behind his eyes that he wants to be rehabilitated, we think he is actually waiting for it, we think he is one light bulb moment away from realizing that people are good. You currently have to chase him down and handle him with care until he is in your arms. Once you have him in your arms, his fight goes away and he can be worked with.

 

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting this baby, please fill out an application. They currently are fixed, up to date on shots, wormings, preventatives and are microchipped. Adoption fee is $188 ($175 Adoption Fee + $13 Lifetime Registration Fee for Microchip), applications can be filled out at this link. https://www.petstablished.com/adoption_form/10167/generic .We cannot guarantee breed or size when full grown.

 

Due to our current situation, with more great applicants than we have available puppies and young adults, we are no longer accepting applications from people that are over 150 miles away. Exceptions will be made on dogs over the age of 3, special needs dogs and direct referrals from our volunteers.

animal.description:
Bonita's litter was so excited to be born into this world that their momma didn't even make it to Omaha before she went into labor! Pregnant and alone, Bonita was rescued from an overcrowded Oklahoma shelter euthanization list and started having puppies during transport, which was abruptly halted. Once momma and 11 puppies were safe and approved for travel, they completed the journey to their Muddy Paws foster home. Starting 2/28/21 these babies will be looking for homes ready to embark on the great adventure of raising a puppy!

Since this puppy may be too young to be altered at the time of adoption, the adopters will be provided with a voucher to have the puppy altered and microchipped by the time he is 6 months of age. This must be done at Nebraska Humane Society. If you prefer to take the puppy to your own vet, we will pay a PORTION of the cost ($69) to your vet of choice.

The suggested adoption donation for this puppy is $450. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Meet Rose, the elegant thirty-eight pound approximately 4-year-old foxhound. Rose is gentle and not a barker, and she would be best in a home with a fenced in backyard. The Foxhound is a sweet dog with a lot of patience, but bred for activity. They are not recommended for novice dog owners, especially those living in urban areas. Thus we are not adopting her to apartment owners. This is an intelligent, active breed that will find some way to occupy themselves, and in a potentially destructive manner, if they don't have space or time for running. So, a fenced in backyard with a doggy door is ideal. She is great with all humans including kids. She is both dog and cat friendly. She, like all rescues, will need decompression time and patience in a new environment. We do not know if she is housebroken yet, but she would learn quickly when given proper direction and guidance. She will be up to date on all her shots and spayed by the time she arrives on Sunday, January 24. To adopt Rose please visit our website www.peace4paws.org and fill out an adoption application. Thank you. 


Dog Size Guidelines:
Small: 25 lbs and under (11 kg)
Medium: 26–60 lbs (12 – 27 kg)
Large: 61–100 lbs (28 – 45 kg)
Extra Large: 101 lbs or more (46 kg)

animal.description: Kissy is a very loving dog. She likes to chase squirrels in the yard and snuggle. I think mostly she will want to sit on the couch with you and have her pet her belly.Kissy has had a very hard start to life and as a result he is scared. We pulled her from a scary animal control with her puppies. Any new little change makes her nervous such as wearing a coat when you didn't before. Kissy is going to need a very patient owner. She is not going to bond with you immediately. It will take weeks. However once she trusts you she is all yours. She shows her gratitude and love. I do not think she would do well in a home full of rambunctious children because of how scared she is. She has never been aggressive or nipped. She is fabulous with cats. I have not tested her with my dogs but with slow introductions I think she would do well with a doggie friend. She is 25 lbs. and house trained. She may have an accident every now and then but it is a rare occasion. Fenced yard required. She walks well on a leash if she is't scared where she is going.

I am approximately one year old and I love other dogs but foster momma doesn't think he'd be good with cats because I like to chase the ones that come into our yard. I love my foster sister because she likes to play and rough house with me and she understands that when I'm happy I show all my teeth and smile and she doesn't get scared. She understands I'm just really really happy. Foster momma says I have some insecurity issues and I guess I do...but hey I was a puppy during COVID-19 so I missed some pretty important milestones! I get scared around new people. I don't growl or anything but they terrify me and I require lots of love to calm down. I also have a tinsy issue with food that I am working on. I can take treats with other dogs and can even stand with the pack while you serve up the food but it's best if I eat alone and have a bit of a time-out after I finish. I'm working on it and the more I work on it the more confident I become and the less of an issue it is.So the things I want in a forever family would be a doggy brother or sister to play and rough-house with. m i'mpetite maybe 30 to 40 lbs so someone that size or a little bigger would be great. A family to love me and be patient while they work on my little issue would be fantastic. In return I promise to potty outside once you show me where. To be a lovable cuddly family member that requires lots of stuffies (to unstuff!) and chew toys and to be the best Poke-a-Dot you've ever seen! Will you be my forever? requires a fence
animal.name: Dot

animal.description: Sergeant is a lovable energetic and young male Great Pyrenees. He is somewhat shy around new people and may bark at them but he is not aggressive. He is slow to make new friends but once he does he's as playful as any other dog might be. He loves to chase squirrels and just about anything else including birds that he feels are in his territory;. As most dogs of his breed and disposition Sergeant is most satisfied running in wide open spaces with different things to explore and play with. He can be stubborn at times but only out of nervousness and not out of spite. Given the effort he would make a good companion for someone with plenty of fenced in land and the patience to earn his trust. He is not a house dog and would do best with a confident and gentle human that is comfortable spending time outdoors and wants make him part of the pack.

Profile: Hunter is an estimated 3 year old male German Shepherd Dog with a stellar personality and a lotta love to give. He currently weighs 96 lbs but would look great around 90 lbs (and we're working on it). Hunter is living with other dogs and is very tolerant good (tolerant!) with males and females. He has also been friendly with children he has met. He can be territorial on leash without proper leadership, but will thrive with a breed savvy owner who wants a balanced, friendly GSD with a good temperament. Hunter is house-trained and working on crate-training, and would prefer an owner or family who is home more often than not.

Note: We will only consider single family residences (no apartments/condos) for Hunter. Dog experience is required: No first-time dog owners.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online: www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

History: Hunter was transferred from a Seattle area shelter due to kennel stress.

animal.description:
So Bear was adopted out as a puppy in March 2019.  Sadly, his owner of 70 years  of age passed and the family has several animals of their own.  They were very sad and reluctant to give him up,  but they already have a full house.  The previous owner didn t have other animals by choice.

This boy is energetic.  Older children would be fine, but not a toddler as he loves to run when he gets in his yard.  He does need to be taught no jumping on humans, etc.   Positive training of course to be rewarded with a treat!  As far as other dogs, it is unknown.  My guess is that he would be dog selective and reactive if he comes in contact with a dog that has an alpha demeanor.   He s a shepherd  so I believe he would make an awesome protector.

I will also have him heartworm tested if there is no current test in his medical file.  As soon as this is known,  I will update!  My guess if that he s negative....but we ll find out for certain!

animal.description:
NAME: Clyde
BREED: Shih Tzu 
BIRTHDAY: 2008
WEIGHT: 20lbs
ADOPTION FEE: $250

Don't let the grumpy face fool you- Clyde is sweet and gentle despite all he's been through. This long fellow had a home once, and a mom who loved him but just couldn't afford to care for him. He was suffering from eye and ear infections and had a huge mass on his side. The mass ruptured, got infected, and animal control removed Clyde from his home. A stinky dog with a hole in his side was not safe in the Philly shelter, but luckily we have friends there and they asked us to help Clyde. And of course we did!

Clyde gets along just fine with dogs, cats, and new people. He is almost completely blind so he is nervous at first, but warms up with kind words and lots of petting. Unfortunately most of his time with us has been spent doing wound care (his cancerous ruptured mass was removed and Clyde is now cancer-free!), and treating his eye and ear infections, so we didn't get off to a great start of making him feel comfortable mentally. However, now that he is finally healing up we are making progress with earning Clyde's trust and letting him know his suffering is over. Although he gets around pretty well, Clyde does need help going outside and coming back in after going potty. He will need a patient family who is willing to work on his house training and give him daily eye medications to prevent dry eye (a common Shih Tzu issue.) Clyde will need a home without small children.

animal.description:
This beautiful young (15 months old) dog came from a home where he was loved, and yet there were issues. His mistress, a young woman who adored him, realized that she didn’t have the skills needed, and the rest of the family (her parents) weren’t on board with regard to consistency, structure, and rules, and she didn’t have control over how he was being treated (rough treatment by the man in the home). 

Bean is a sweet boy who lacks confidence and needs an understanding human (Rottweiler experience a must) to provide clear, consistent rules to help him be the best he can be. Overall he's proven to be an easy, low key dog, very mellow and not high energy at all. He adores being with his human and an ideal home for him would be someone who is retired (quiet home without young kids) or maybe someone who works from home, or can take him along. Someone who would like to talk a leisurely walk with him in the morning and spend the rest of the day hanging out. 

He's still getting over some of the treatment he had in his prior home and can be very unsure of himself, slow and tentative. So far he's been very friendly with everyone he meets, but is cautious when meeting men. He's been around horses, chickens, and the barn cats without much fuss, and seems to have a fairly low prey drive.  He just wants to be loved and to lie at your feet adoringly.

He’s good with other dogs, including small breed dogs (his sister was a shih tzu), but wants to dominate one of the other male dogs in his foster home. He’s very responsive and nonchallenging to humans, with basic obedience and is looking for consistent guidance and confidence from his human. 

This boy has SO much potential and is ripe for becoming your next nose work titleholder, or barn hunt champion, or simply your best walking buddy. He’s young and has so much to learn…and to give. This guy is truly a diamond in the ‘ruff’ and we are excited for the bright future ahead. 

Go to  https://spdrdogs.org/rescue-referral/how-to-adopt/ to fill out an adoption application for Bean.

Washington State only - no interstate transports (although we will consider Oregon and Idaho applicants).

Visit our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/SPDRRottweilerRescue

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Beans is a beautiful bully mix that is looking for the perfect home here in the PNW. Beans is all about that ball life, so if you are looking for a dog that loves fetch he's your guy! While Beans is active and up for anything, he is also perfectly happy to snuggle up and snore the afternoon away. Beans is incredibly food motivated and eager to please! He is crate trained, but does have some minor separation anxiety that presents in the form of whining, not barking. Beans is also house trained, and does well on leash with a training collar. Beans does have some leash reactivity, but he has drastically improved that behavior and with continued training we are confident he will be an excellent canine citizen. His ideal home would have bully breed experience, a securely fenced yard, be able to provide consistent structure and training, and a comfy couch for snuggling up at the end of the day. Though Beans has played with other dogs he would be best as an only dog with no kids under the age of 12 due to his size and strength.

DNA: 50% Amstaff 20% Aussie 20% Collie

Adoption Info:
Adoption fee is $400 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online:
www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

Meet Emery #2, an 8 year old yellow Labrador eager and ready for his forever home! Emery is a full-sized lab weighing approximately 70 lbs. Emery is a total sweetheart and just as handsome as can be! Emery is working on his leash-walking skills and is housebroken. He is also crate-trained. Emery loves water, so his forever home should be ready for water activities. He will chase the hose, because he loves to bite at the water! Emery is a bit nervous at first and once he knows he is safe, he will be your best friend. Emery gets along great with other dogs. Please ask us all about this fantastic senior; we've promised him the perfect forever home!

For additional information about Emery #2 please email Shana Luzusky at shana2576@gmail.com. 

IMPORTANT INFORMATION: We receive many questions about our adoption process from potential adopters, most of which can be answered by viewing our "Adopt a Lab" page on our full service website, https://labs4rescue.com/.   To expedite the process, please follow the step-by-step instructions outlined and submit an adoption application listing 3-5 dogs of interest. Please hurry as your new best friend is waiting for you!

ADOPTION FEES: $345 non-refundable adoption fee for all vet expenses (spay/neuter, shots, etc.) and transportation to ensure your lab gets to you in a safe, professional manner. All fees may be paid using PayPal, cashier's checks, or money orders. Labs4rescue does not accept personal checks for adoption fees. All adopters must pay their Labs4rescue adoption fee prior to the rescue shipping their dog.

Residents of Massachusetts or New Hampshire are required to pay an additional $125 fee, which defrays the cost of their state's mandatory 48 hour isolation and examination by a licensed veterinarian.

***********************************************************************
 MEET KASEY!!

Sadly, Kasey was roaming in the woods out in the country in the middle of nowhere with a group of dogs and they would come up on someone's property.
 
They would not approach the people so they set up a trap and caught her. 

Apparently, there are more dogs (and coyotes) out there that they are trying to capture. 
 
Kasey is a year old and weighs about 22lbs and is a very unique looking little low rider. (Corgi/Schnauzer/Jack Russell blend???) 

Kasey is totally housebroken and has great house manners and does not need to be crated!

 Kasey is very sweet but also very shy and skittish and calm and quiet. She is starting to come out of her shell (and gives kisses) but she needs someone with patience to give her the time she needs to blossom. 

KASEY IS A GREAT DOG!!!

She is indifferent to other dogs but would do best as an only dog. Currently prefers to hide behind a chair or in a corner but has been really coming out of her shell!

 It seems as if she is not used to the comforts of life and soft blankets or kindness... she has a sad and gentle nature about her. 

She is doing great on the leash!

Sadly, Kasey is heartworm positive and has started treatment which is paid for by Mini Mutts. We expect her to test negative in six months!

Kasey needs a new life!!

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Dustin Henderson but all my friends call me Dusty! I'm a one-year-old, 55- pound, Spaniel & Border Collie mix (I think!). I have some wonderful qualities and I'm a very handsome doggo, but I also have some behavioral challenges that I am working on and I require an experienced adopter. Please look beyond my handsome pics and read on to learn more about me.

Here are all the ways I'm an awesome dog:

- I'm house trained and crate trained. I'm working on my leash training and making great progress!

- I love to get outside for walking, hiking, and playing fetch. I also enjoy napping afterward just as much.

- I'm very smart, treat-motivated, and eager to please so I pick up on training quickly.

- Once I know & trust you, I'm a sweet and lovable boy. I give kisses and love to be pet.

- I like playing with other dogs around my size whose energy & demeanor are a complement to my own.

Here are the areas where my behavior is a work in progress and why I need an adopter with dog behavior experience:

- I have "stranger danger". New people are scary to me so I try to be even scarier by barking and lunging. Once I know and trust you, I am a lovable, sweet boy but it will take me several meetings to get to that point with a new person.

- I have some anxiety. It doesn't bother me too much when things are quiet & peaceful. But sometimes when things around me are busy or too active, I get a little overwhelmed.

- Because of my behavior, I need a quiet home with adults only.

I may not be a perfect dog, but I'm still a very good boy. I love the people in my life who I know & trust and they love me too. I'm sure there is someone out there for me who will teach me that life is not so scary and will help me to build my confidence, trust humans, and be the bestest doggo I can be!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

Matthew is an approximately six-month old Shar Pei-Lab mix who’s very active and has so much love to give.  He was found wandering in the woods and his foster family is working with him on the basic skills of potty training, etiquette and play, but Matthew will likely need some additional formal training due to his high energy level and lack of experience in a domestic environment.

Matthew is very people-centered. He loves cuddling on the couch, happily accepts belly rubs and is always craving treats! He has been a very fast learner when it comes to potty training and is an extremely attentive listener. We expect he will grow to be a very obedient boy.

Due to his alpha personality, Matthew would probably do best in a home currently without other pets. However, Matthew does like other dogs and we believe he could eventually thrive with a patient family willing to properly integrate him with another pup. Since he is still so young, Matthew would also do best with a family with older children.

Matthew is a beautiful dog with an even more beautiful heart. Despite the adversity he faced, he is a sweet, playful and loving boy who will make a wonderful life companion.

If you are interested in meeting Matthew, please fill out an application via our website at https://therescueproject.net/adoption-application and we will get back to you via email once your application has been reviewed.  If you have further questions please feel free to reach out to us at adoptionstrp@gmail.com

Matthew's adoption fee is $150 and includes age appropriate vaccines, spay/neuter, microchip, deworm, and heartworm testing.

animal.description:
Edison is a senior but don't let that fool you - this old guy does not spend his days napping. Edison is alert and excited for each new day. Whether that be accompanying you in the car on your errands, or just following you around the house, he just wants to be where you are, by your side.

Edison walks nicely on the leash, and is always excited to go for a walk. Out and about he's friendly and curious, and seems very keen to meet other dogs. We're not too sure how he feels about cats just yet, but in his current foster home he lives with a parrot and he has no interest in him at all.

He is happy in his crate, is perfectly house trained, and quiet in the home. We're not sure Edison can bark, we have never heard him, but he does make an adorable old man grunt when he wants your attention.

He is also clearly a little hard of hearing, but if you clap or wave your hands around he will realize you want his attention and will come bounding over.

An affectionate and mellow guy, Edison loves to fall asleep with head on your lap. He loves attention and cuddles, and if you stop petting him you might hear one of his famous 'grunts' to request you not to stop!

We can't forget to mention that sweet Edison has a heart shaped head. He really does. He wears his big heart on the outside as well as the inside, we love this guy!

Edison is 8 years old, 62 lbs, and ready for his forever home! Please visit www.liveloveanimalrescue.org to fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
Meet Remy. This handsome boy was found running as a stray in a small town in South Carolina and taken in by a Good Samaritan. They posted him online, had him scanned for a microchip, and contacted Animal Control to see if anyone was looking for him, and found no one. To ensure he would find his true forever home, they contacted Worthy Dog for help.

Remy is currently living in SC in a home with his foster mom and two other dogs, a small Chihuahua and a Lab, and he does well with both. He gets along great with other dogs and really enjoys their company. He's a medium-level energy pup who loves to romp and play and knows how to be mellow inside. Daily activity and exercise is the key to keeping him calm and well behaved.

Like many hound mixes, Remy is a vocal dog and will bark when he gets excited. Because of this, he is not a good fit for a condo or apartment. His foster mom describes him as a playful but gentle pup who is very respectful of your space and the other dogs. He's crate trained and sleeps well through the night, and has been getting better every day at walking on a leash.

We think sweet Remy will make a great family dog. He's social and not shy around new people, and doesn't like being left out - he wants to know where everyone is. We are looking for a fun, active family with another young playful pup in the home.

FOSTER UPDATE - 1/28/21

Remy has really settled in. He likes pet and being close by, so he's starting to hang out with us more now. He loves being wherever his family is and loves playing with the dogs.

He does mouth a bit when excited, but no nipping or biting. He is calm when he meets people, and doesn't try to jump on them right away.

He is significantly better on his leash walking. He takes his treats really well, very gentle. He still has to learn how to play with people so that he isn't as mouthy, but that's improving too.

Remy gets neutered this week and will be ready to come to N. VA on 2/6.

Apply today!

BREED ESTIMATE: Beagle or Hound/Shepherd mix
GENDER: Male
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 40 lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~1.5 to 2 years
COAT TYPE: Medium
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: UTD on shots/neutered/microchipped
LOCATION: Indian Land, SC

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.
