All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.

animal.description:
Dill is a 1 year old male Labrador Retriever mix sweetheart who currently weighs 45 pounds but should be closer to 50-55lbs. He is equal parts playful and cuddly. His favorite things include running around the yard chasing other dogs, snuggling on the couch, and scouring the kitchen floor for snacks. He is so sweet and gives the best kisses.

Dill has a few charming puppy habits such as chewing on shoes, pillows, and clothes if found lying around when he's unsupervised. His foster family is working on breaking the habit. He is also skeptical about stairs at first, but with practice, has learned to go up and down the stairs without issue. He is (mostly) house trained, with the exception of a couple accidents on his first day in the foster home.

Dill is great with humans and other dogs. He absolutely loves his 4-legged foster sister. He is the hyper little brother that consistently nags her to play, but always in a gentle manner.

Dill would do great in any home, but would be best with active owners who can make sure he gets daily exercise and play time. He can also benefit from some basic training and discipline to break a few of his puppy habits. Regardless, he will make any family happy because he is truly a great dog.

If you are interested in adopting Dill please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte is responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

animal.description:
Marilyn is ready for her forever! Get ready to fall in love!

Marilyn came to us a little over two months ago from a shelter in Southern California. Originally she was pulled with her buddy Monroe, but they ended up not being bonded and Monroe quickly found a loving home. Marilyn needed extra time and love. Her time in Southern California was traumatizing and she was in a major funk when she came to her foster home. We cannot stress what a perfect example Marilyn is of rescue dogs who need time and patience and love in order to truly heal and trust and feel safe. 

While Marilyn has made huge progress with the help of her incredible fosters, she still needs a very specific kind of home to thrive.  Marilyn does well with other dogs with slow introductions.  She does not like to be crated. 

While Marilyn is not a “plug and play” dog, she is special, and we have found that the broken ones are often most desperate to give and receive love, and end up becoming our heart dogs. Our namesake was no easy pup, but Dublin grew into the greatest gift. We know that Marilyn is a special girl who needs to find her perfect match. Are you her forever?
Please email 4everyoursrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application.
Adoptions only in Reno, Sacramento, Nevada County, Roseville and Rocklin.

animal.description:
Foster was owned by a local man but kept escaping so he decided to surrender him to rescue. He was born January 3, 2018 along with his brother Bananas (also available for adoption). Both boys are extremely sweet and ready to find their furever families!

If you are interested in pursuing an adoption and you live in Texas , please complete the application (links provided below). The process includes a vet check, calling references and doing a home visit. 

http://www.texassleddogrescue.org/web_documents/tsdr_application.pdf
or
https://www.formstack.com/forms/?1632205-WX2Zb144ZP

Please note the following:
We rarely do out of state adoptions.  (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience and will require same adoption process.)
Children in the home or that visit often must be at least 6 years of age. (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience.)
Adoption donation is due at the time of adoption.  Puppies under 1 year are $300. Dogs 1 year to 7 years are $200 and dogs over 7 years are $150.  As this is a donation, it will be non-returnable if dog is returned to rescue.
Dogs are not placed on a "first come, first serve" basis but rather the best home for the dog. 
All dogs placed by TSDR will be:
spayed/neutered
vaccinated for distemper/parvo, rabies, and bordetella
heartworm tested and treated if needed
microchipped
other vetting as deemed needed
New owners will receive copies of all available vet information and must agree to keep them current on all of the above.

animal.description:
Bananas was owned by a local man but kept escaping so he decided to surrender him to rescue. He was born January 3, 2018 along with his brother Foster (also available for adoption). Both boys are extremely sweet and ready to find their furever families!

If you are interested in pursuing an adoption and you live in Texas , please complete the application (links provided below). The process includes a vet check, calling references and doing a home visit. 

http://www.texassleddogrescue.org/web_documents/tsdr_application.pdf
or
https://www.formstack.com/forms/?1632205-WX2Zb144ZP

Please note the following:
We rarely do out of state adoptions.  (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience and will require same adoption process.)
Children in the home or that visit often must be at least 6 years of age. (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience.)
Adoption donation is due at the time of adoption.  Puppies under 1 year are $300. Dogs 1 year to 7 years are $200 and dogs over 7 years are $150.  As this is a donation, it will be non-returnable if dog is returned to rescue.
Dogs are not placed on a "first come, first serve" basis but rather the best home for the dog. 
All dogs placed by TSDR will be:
spayed/neutered
vaccinated for distemper/parvo, rabies, and bordetella
heartworm tested and treated if needed
microchipped
other vetting as deemed needed
New owners will receive copies of all available vet information and must agree to keep them current on all of the above.

animal.description:
*******WE ONLY ACCEPT APPLICATIONS WITHIN A 50 MILES RADIUS OF MURFREESBORO, TN******- (some exceptions but must be outstanding home for certain dogs)

Adam West is 4 years old, 12lbs. Great with other dogs, and is crate trained. He is still working on perfecting house training. Doesn’t have many accidents. He’ll readily go outside to go potty, he loves it outside. He loves chew toys and likes to follow his foster everywhere but loves to sleep on your lap. He will need a fenced yard. He likes kids but would do best in a home with older kids  (teens). He does like to sneak out open doors just to go outside for fun so would need to be watched when people are coming and going out exterior doors. 

Adoption fees is $200 for dogs over 8 months. If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.middletennesseetreasures.com.

Our dogs and cats are kept in foster homes with volunteers who share their homes with these animals until the right adoptive home is found. These foster homes evaluate for temperament and also work on basic training with the dogs. Our dogs and cats have been seen by a vet, brought up to date on vaccinations, micro-chipped, heartworm tested, cleared of parasites and spayed or neutered if 6 months or older. 

The first step in adopting from Middle Tennessee Treasures is to complete an adoption application.(http://www.middletennesseetreasures.com/adoption/) Vet references are usually called first. When we contact your vet we ask about current and past pets (both dogs and cats). We ask if all animals are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, seen on a yearly basis and whether dogs are on heartworm preventative. Personal references are called and finally a home visit is set up. The purpose of the home visit to meet you, your family, and any pets you may have. It also allows us to see what kind of dog or cat would be the best fit for your home. 

This screening process helps to ensure that each rescued dog is placed in a loving, safe, and permanent home. We do not place our dogs on a first come, first serve basis, but according to the needs of the dog and family.

FAST FACTS:
*3 Years Old - 44 Pounds
*Shy, Needs Patient Adopters
*Dog Friendly - Would Love a Dog Companion
*Crate Trained
*Working on Potty Training
*Training Required

BIO:
Hey o! My name is Molley, and good golly am I going to make a great companion for the patient family that gives me a chance to thrive! I previously lived in a small cage being bred for my puppies, so I am just starting to learn about the big, wide world around me and need humans who will give me time to settle in and feel safe. I do great with other dogs and think it would be a big bonus to have a doggie friend in my forever family; I have learned that playing outside in the snow with my canine foster brothers is a lot of fun! It would be nice to have a securely fenced yard to enjoy at my forever home, too. I am crate trained (and consider it a safe space to lounge while I adapt into my new home), but my potty training is a work in progress and I need some patience while I learn this important skill. Speaking of learning, I need a family who will be committed to signing me up for training classes; I think training will help with my confidence and I am eager to learn how to dog. Could you be the person to make my dreams of a loving home and family come true? Then fill out an adoption application soon, please!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

animal.description:
FAST FACTS:
*6 Years Old - 8 Pounds
*Low-Medium Energy
*Dog Friendly - All Sizes!
*Cat Friendly
*Older Children
*Working on Potty Training
*Prefers People Home Often

BIO:
Have you been dreaming a little dream of a sweet, affectionate girl who will never leave your side? My name is Doris, and I am a darling little lady who would love a home with patient people who will go slow with me to help me learn what being pampered and loved is like. I spent the earlier part of my life in a small cage being bred for my puppies, and am finally experiencing life in a cozy home for the first time. I love being near my people once I am comfortable and would appreciate a home where someone is home more often than not so we can spend our time together making each other happy. I'm dog and cat friendly, and would do fine in a home with children old enough to understand to go slow with me and be respectful. I am not a fan of a crate, but do fine in a larger playpen where I have room to move around if you need to leave the house for a while. I am also not potty trained and hope for patience and understanding that this might take me a while to learn. Do you think you could be the special person to help me blossom and provide me with all the love I've dreamed about? Please fill out an adoption application so we can get our happily ever after started!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

*3 Years Old - 38 Pounds
*Medium Energy
*Dog Friendly - Would Prefer a Doggie Companion
*Crate Trained
*Working on Potty Training
*Training Required

BIO:
Greetings, future family! My name is Dorri and I am looking for a patient family who will help me blossom into the confident girl I know I am meant to be! You see, I was previously kept in a small cage and bred for my puppies, so I would thrive with  people who understand that much of the world is brand new to me and I need to learn how to be a dog. Despite my previous circumstances, I am a very sweet babe who loves to snuggle and nap, though I enjoy playtime and running around the yard with my doggie friends, too! In fact, I think I would do best in a home with another dog who will play and nap with me. I also like cuddles with my people, and think I would do fine in a home with children who are old enough to understand I might be shy at first. I am crate trained, but need help with potty training; I am working hard on this skill, but I need some patience while I continue to figure it out. I would love to learn more skills, as well, and would like a family that will commit to signing me up for training. I think training classes will also help with my socialization and confidence, so it could be the first of what I hope are many future adventures! If you think you are the people to help me blossom and provide me the love and comfort I have always dreamed about, please fill out an adoption application!

animal.description:
That's me, It's me, that's me - Jolene!
There's no point in begging because I'm gonna steal your heart, oh man!
That's me, it's me, that's me - Jolene!
I'm gonna take your heart just because I can

My beauty is beyond compare
With a luscious coat of auburn hair
With a smile of sunshine that begs to be seen
I'm a special needs girl that deserves love, you know what I mean?
I'm a calm mannered girl who enjoys pups and play
There is no other girl that competes with me-
I'm Jolene

Meet volunteer favorite and absolute sweetheart Jolene!  This cutie is a 54lb 7-8 year old mixed breed pooch, who enjoys snuggling (and snoring!) on the couch but is also up for walking around the neighborhood.  Jolene is good with the trifecta...other dogs, cats, and kids and even attended a Christmas event in her native Texas.  Though well controlled (she has yet to have one with us) Jolene is on medication for seizures and will need to continue that throughout her life.  We also recommend a joint supplement for some arthritis in her back legs though she doesn't let that stop her.

Jolene, Jolene, Jolene adopt her today by email info@joyrides.org

animal.description:
Meet Spot, who is looking for a foster or foster to adopt home.

Ready to have your heart melted, meet big hunk of nothing but love is Spot. He is a large 99lb Mastiff mix around 2 years old ready for a foster family of his own. Spot rightly has been named as he has one black spot right above his tail that gives him a very unique appearance. Spot is extremely sweet but is looking for a foster who understands his breed as he is very devoted once he bonds to his people and gets a little insecure at times. He will need a strong leader who is experienced with training large breed dogs and a kid free home. Spot is already house and crate trained, plus knows how to sit on command and paw too. Spot would love to be the only dog in the home soaking up all the love. He may do well in a home with submissive female dog but his family will need to understand this will take time, patience and training as Spot can be selective on his doggie friends. Spot has not been around cats. Spot is truly a wonderful boy with so much love to give. He just needs to right person and home to thrive, Apply to foster Spot today at www.underhoundrailroad.org.

Spot is currently being fostered in North Carolina. Please message us with any questions about our foster or foster to adopt program.

Brady likes to spend his time going for walks, hanging outside, and getting treats! He is looking for a home outside of the city, ideally with a fenced yard for him to roam and play.

animal.description:
Ahoy, Maties! My name is Captain, and I’m a 2-year old yellow lab mix that weighs about 61 pounds. I still need to gain about 5-10 pounds…but I don’t think that should be that hard to do. 

I am full of love and have adapted to my foster home pretty quickly.  I have a furry foster sibling in my home right now and would be okay if my furrever home has a dog or I’d be completely fine on my own. To be honest, I’m more concerned with human attention that attention from other dogs. One thing I do need is a secure, fenced-in yard.  I am pretty sneaky, so we need to make sure I don’t find any escape routes. When I first arrived at my foster home, I did not play with toys but I’m slowly coming around to how much fun they are. 

I am already housebroken and potty-trained. I do not need to be crated as I am not a destructive guy and if I do get crated I spend the whole time plotting my escape.  I am ready to find my furrever home and since I’m “move-in” ready, I hope it will be a quick journey to find my new family.

For this to be a successful adoption, Captain MUST HAVE:
No invisible fence

If you are interested in meeting me, please contact LOLIN for a meet and greet.

If you are interested in adopting, please go to our website at www.lolin.org and click on Adoption Process along the left-hand side.  From there, you can submit an Adoption Application to be considered for this dog.  You MUST be an approved applicant to meet LOLIN dogs.  There is no central location or hours to meet dogs.

animal.description:
Boston and Pepe are a bonded pair*** will not separate***

Boston
Bonded Pair
Labrador Retriever mix
Boston is a Labrador Retriever mix. His shorter legs suggest Corgi; and the shape of his head, spotted tongue, and happy disposition suggest Lab.
Boston came to Colorado from Texas when the adult’s son went to foster care and he and Peppe lost their primary caretaker. The household had many cats and it should make for an easy meet-and-greet if there is a cat in his new home.
Boston is a happy dog and will be happiest when allowed to play in a fenced-in yard with Peppe and when taught basic commands. He loves exercising by roughhousing with Peppe outside, and both know to stop when you tell them enough. He appreciates ending his day by snuggling with his foster mom.
Boston is a nice dog who kindly knows not to jump up on kids or adults. He takes to riding inside the back of a car naturally, and his appreciating your help lifting him up tells you he is trusting.


$100 refundable after successful completion of approved obedience classes.

animal.description:
Cashew and her five sisters were surrendered to an overcrowded shelter in northern Louisiana. We believe they are golden retriever mixes. She’s about 20 pounds currently and expected to be in the medium to large size range when full grown. Cashew is good with other dogs and kids (we’re not sure about cats, but expect that she’d do just fine). Cashew is microchipped and up to date on vaccines. She’ll be spayed at 6 months old. She’s doing great with house and kennel training!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Meet Evander! Yes, as in Holyfield...

Evander came to us from a local shelter where his owner surrendered him. He came in with the injury to his ear and this is the way he came to CARES when we pulled him from the shelter. Unfortunately too much time has passed to try to suture it. The vet advised us to simply leave it alone and it will heal. We told Evander this makes him extra special!

Evander is a young male - about 1-2 years old. He is crate trained and has been good about outside potty. He came in a bit timid when being handled so we are still getting used to walking on a leash. Sporting a beautiful black coat with just a bit of white on his chest, Evander looks to be a beautiful Dachshund mix. This boy is full grown at only 11.5 pounds. 

Evander has been good with all the dogs here; however he would be best suited for a home with no cats. 

Evander has an appointment on Thursday for neuter surgery, chipping and to finish up his vaccines. We will also get a closer age estimate at that time. Evander will be ready for his new home this Friday! 

Evander is healthy, fully vetted and ready  to leave for his forever home soon so we are taking applications now! His wish list consists of an inside forever home with a big fenced yard for playtime, a home with lots of toys and another doggy friend for play time and pet parents who understand the time commitment that a new dog requires. Adopters who are retired or work-from-home parents are ideal as they have the time to spend with the pet. Adopters committed to doing a 6 week basic obedience class to ensure Evander's successful transition to his new home would also a plus (and to ensure the new puppy parent's education level). If you think you have the perfect home for Evander, contact us at info.caresga@gmail.com for an adoption application. We adopt up north and all over so please ask for details. $350 adoption fee and a vet reference is required to ensure a great home (this means you have had a pet so we can call to verify their level of care). Eligibility for adoption means your current or past pets are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines and on monthly heartworm and flea prevention. Please be aware that we do not allow shock collars (ie underground fences) or "pens" as an alternative for a fenced yard.

We do our best to place our rescue pets in the very best homes. Please be aware that we have an application which also includes required vet records showing your existing pets are current on preventative medical care. Puppy adopters please take note that we generally try to place our puppies into homes where at least one parent is retired/stay at home/works from home to ensure the puppy gets enough attention and training (puppies cannot hold it all day in a crate) so please have a plan ready when contacting us. For safety reasons, we try not to place small dogs or puppies in families with children under 5 (there may be exceptions depending on situation).

Adoption fees vary based on breed, size and age. Some pets, smaller dogs for example, may have a higher than normal adoption fee but we will alert you if there is a variance. Dogs rescued from China always have a higher adoption fee. Adoption fees help our group offset PART of the cost of rescuing, rehabilitating, and getting the pet healthy so they can go on to find a loving home with someone willing to give them a second chance at life. This amount includes each animal being current on age appropriate vaccinations including DHPPL, bordetella, influenza, rabies, and boosters when appropriate. De-wormed for any internal parasites (round worms, hook worms, tape worms and whipworms) with Drontal Plus, 4DX tested heart-worm negative (if positive, they are treated), tested negative for tick borne diseases, spayed/neutered, implanted with a micro-chip and have been examined by a veterinarian to certify that they are healthy. Any other known health issues are treated as well prior to adoption (examples: UTI, broken bones, contagious infections, dental cleanings, etc). All animals are also on a regime of flea and heartworm medication every month. Lifetime registration for the micro-chip is included in each adoption fee. In addition, each adopter will go home with a fitted collar, tags, a bag of dog food the pet has been on, copies of all vet history, and an adoption kit filled with valuable information and coupons as well as other various treats or toys as promotions become available. All puppy adoptions include two puppy training books, the Puppy Primer & Way To Go by Patricia McConnell, and all adult adoptions go home with Love Has No Age Limit by Patricia McConnell to help ensure a smooth transition for your new family member.

We ask that you consider an additional donation on top of this pet's adoption fee. This money will go directly into our Adoption Fund to be used exclusively for rescuing and caring for other pets in need. Many pets we take in have very high vet bills to get them healthy and adoptable for the public - much higher than their adoption fees. We receive no government funding and rely solely on donations from our community and caring adopters to continue our rescue efforts!

animal.description:
Mr. Jack is a 9 year old Jack Russell Terrier mix.  Jack came to the rescue after his owner passed away.  We know a little about Jack's past but not much.  He was originally found as a stray when he was believed to be a year old.  He did well in the home with the woman but was protective of her from the man.  Due to this, Jack is requiring a home with a single owner, preferably, his own lady friend!

Jack has proven to be very sweet with the volunteers but has been known to be bossy when he doesn't get his way.  Jack is extremely intelligent and knows how to push the boundaries.  He is very food motivated so we think this boy could learn some new tricks!   He will require some structure, patience and lots of activity!  Don't let Jack's age fool ya!  He is still a very lively fella.  Jack would not do well in a home with other dogs, small critters, or children.  

Jack is healthy but does have a slight heart murmur.  We don't believe this to negatively affect his life.  If you are local to the area, a single lady, active, and live in a quite home, Jack could be your new companion!  Please visit our website, www.crcpa.org, to learn more about or adoption process and complete an application.

animal.description:
Jiminy needs a home with:

- no children under the age of 16
- no apartments
- fenced yard

Meet Jiminy! Jiminy is an adorable 1 year old Basenji/Cattledog mix with the most audacious personality! He absolutely loves his toys, especially soft squeaky toys, and will toss them around and pounce on them all day long. Jiminy loves to run zoomies in the yard and would do best being supervised while he's outside so he's being as safe as possible. He's got some real fast speed and doesn't have any brakes which makes him the perfect running or hiking buddy. Even though he's young, Jiminy already knows 'sit' and could use a patient owner to teach him everything he'll need to know in order to be the best dog he can be. He would love to explore his surroundings and keeps his nose to the ground when he's out and about. Jiminy needs a home with a fully fenced in yard because adventuring without a buddy can be dangerous and he might not want to wait for his family to come with him. He also needs a home with no children under the age of 16 because his energy could be a little too much for young kiddos. If you're looking for an energetic, fox-eared companion to spend your days with, adopt Jiminy today!

If you're interested in adopting Jiminy, please email a completed adoption application to adoptions@kitsap-humane.org. Adoption applications and more information about our adoption process can be found on our website here: https://www.kitsap-humane.org/adopt/how-to-adopt/. Once your application has been received, you will be placed in line to have your application reviewed. All applicants are pre-screened over the phone, and then are scheduled for a time to come in and meet the dog at the shelter. animal.description:
Cooper (aka Coop) is a sweet & friendly Beagle/Terrier mix who is 8 years old and weighs 55 lbs.  His current family needs to re-home him, so please read his bio below and contact his dad Daniel directly at hunter8285@gmail.com or 850-217-7299 if you'd like to get more information about Coop and possibly adopt this sweet boy! 

Cooper is a relatively laid-back dog. He needs a home where he is given daily walks and/or a fenced in yard to roam around. He walks relatively well on a leash. He isn't needy in the sense that he doesn't need a lot of physical touch.  Our smaller dog does, but Coop is happy to just be in the same room with you. He is content with laying at your feet. He is loyal, food driven, and a great protector. His nickname is Agent Dale Cooper because he likes to police things. If you get up fast or react quickly he will jump to his feet and start barking. He knows basic commands like sit, stay, down, release, and heel (sometimes). He is kennel trained and house broken. Our dogs have been taught to go to their kennels to be fed and they also know what you mean when you say it is time to go to bed. Cooper doesn't have any history of chewing up things that don't belong to him, at least with us. We were told he would get into trash cans but we simply bought trash cans with lids. 

We have owned him for almost 4 years. We took him from a family who no longer wanted him. At that time, he lived with an older dog and there were some serious food aggression issues. We had to work with him a good bit to break him of the food aggression. He's been quite receptive to that and it's evident that we have built rapport with him. We keep the kitchen area blocked off so he cannot grab stuff off of the counter. Cooper was often tethered to a couch or chair in his previous home, which has caused some trauma for him to work through. To add to it all, about 2 years ago he was attacked by a pitbull. Our smaller dog was present and was subsequently chased by another dog present during the attack. Neither of our dogs have quite bounced back personality wise from that trauma. The trauma presents itself within Cooper when he sees a dog that resembles a pitbull. He becomes vocal and can be difficult to manage on a leash. Easiest is to redirect him and take him a different direction. It can be interesting because other times he is non-reactive to other dogs barking or in backyards while we are walking. It does feel unfair for Coop to stay with us because our smaller dog requires so much attention, we have a 20 month old son, and we are expecting another child in April. Cooper is older and needs a quieter and less chaotic place to stay. 

Coop enjoys going for walks either on the road or on a trail. If he could be an only dog that would be preferred. He does deal with some anxiety that flares up in the form of obsessively licking his paws. I think some of this is nervous energy with how busy and chaotic things can get around our house. He has truly been a wonderful dog for us but we also know that he deserves to have more attention than what he currently gets in our home.

Coop is neutered and current on vaccines & preventatives as of 10/2020. He is a very good boy!

Good with other dogs
House trained

animal.description:
Brisco is everyone's idea of the perfect little Shih-Tzu, but he has some healing to do. He would do best with a retired female, as that is what he is used to. He is very attached to his foster mom, and he will be a loyal companion. He will need a gentle patient person to work with him. He needs a quiet home. He is very shy. He is insecure, he is still mourning for the loss of his first home. 
Brisco needs work on his potty training. This dog has not been abused in any way, he has been loved. He's just extremely sensitive and fearfuI of new environments. 
I am inclined to say that if you have not worked as a foster for a dog rescue, or have other extensive dog experience, you may not be the person for this dog. We are being very careful, as we do not want Brisco to be any more traumatized than he already is. His next home has got to be his forever home. 
Brisco is 5 years old. He will need professional grooming about every six weeks. He weighs (guessing) about 15 pounds. You must have a nice secured fenced yard. 
Please fill out an application first if you are interested.
This dog will only be adopted in Tucson, so we can monitor his progress more easily.

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rotti & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secured, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Brisco or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.

animal.description: Mason is what I would call a great traveler dog.  He was owned by a man that kept him tied to his front porch in a rural area.  When his owner went away, Mason was unleashed and left to wander amongst the neighbors who fed him and watched over him. Sometimes, this would be for weeks.  Mason is so people friendly and he is also aware of being nice to other dogs as his habit of wandering the neighborhoods made him be.  He is what we believe, after looking him over, and with his size of approximately 40lbs, to be a cattle dog mix. He is approx. 4 years old.  He really needs a home of his own where he is a part of a family and lives inside, instead of outside. He hates being confined in our kennels and balks when having to come back inside after a nice long walk.  Please consider this boy to add to your family.

We are always looking for fosters. If you are curious on how you can be one please contact rescueme93@yahoo.com for more information.

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Look at this sweet, loving face just asking you to “take me home”. Baxter is a vey handsome  9 1/2 y/o,  Rat Terrier mix.  He’s a very quiet boy with the nicest disposition you could ask for. He gets along with other dogs, doesn’t mind cats and loves to be close to his people. He’s crate trained but prefers to be where his person is. 

Baxter has some special needs that lots of love, exercise and some medications will be needed. He is overweight ( has lost 4 pounds already) and has diabetes ( requires 2 shots a day). He’s an easy dog to love and care for and will make an excellent companion for nice slow walks and for cuddling on your lap. No small children please.

If you are interested in Meeting Baxter, he will be available at times for meet and greets  at Petsmart, Utica on Saturdays from 11 am until 3 pm. Additional times may be scheduled with an approved application.

Both online and pdf applications are available online at
http://members.petfinder.com/~MI730/ . The pdf can be printed, scanned and emailed to rescueme93@yahoo.com .
(Copy and Paste http://members.petfinder.com/~MI730/ into browser).

PetSmart is resuming on site adoptions on Saturdays with a limited number of animals. Personal meet and greets will continue to be scheduled offsite with an approved app. only.

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Both online and PDF application are available online at http://members.petfinder.com/~MI730/ under the links section on the left.

We show most of our adoptable pets at PetSmart, Utica, each Saturday from 11 to 3. If you are interested in a particular pet, we suggest you email: rescueme93@yahoo.com to see if that pet will be there.

Applications are approved on the basis of the best and most appropriate home for the animal, not on a first come, first served basis. On site adoption available to pre-approved applicants only.

Adoption Fees 
Senior 		: 9 years & up $100-$175 
Adult  		: 2 years to 8 years  $250
Young adult	: 6 months to 2 years $275 
Puppies		: 6 weeks to 6 months $300

Adoption fees go towards vaccines, heartworm prevention/testing, flea/tick prevention, spay/neuter and other medical problems that may arise.

MMAR is an all volunteer, foster based, 501 (c) 3, non profit organization. Without your donation, wonderful pets like these have to be passed by because we cannot afford their care.

If you would like to donate please send donation to: MMAR Box 180155 Utica, MI 48318

Donate online at http://members.petfinder.com/~MI730/  .

Please email us at rescueme93@yahoo.com for additional information or to set up special appointments.

animal.description: Jonah is a approximately 1 1/2 - 2 year old boy who looks like a cattle dog / aussie mix. He's kind of a shorter guy. Jonah loves people and loves treats. He came into rescue from the shelter because he had an injury to his left rear leg. The shelter vet thought he had a broken bone. Turns out his hip was dislocated. The best solution for Jonah was an FHO surgery. This removes the head of the femur bone so he doesn't have bone rubbing and allows him to gain use of his leg again. Jonah had his surgery before Christmas. Rested and recovered and is now enjoying special time at his water rehab. Jonah is getting his spunk back is improving daily in how much he uses his leg. He even tries a bit of running and jumping. Jonah does best with female dogs and dogs that are smaller than him. He's a pretty easy going guy who would love a family of his own to enjoy.

animal.description:
What can we say? Miki is a chihuahua and comes with a chihuahua attitude.

She's 4 years old and 4.5 pounds.  So she deserves to have all the attitude in the world she wants to have.

Because of her teeny tiny size, we will not place her in a home with another dog over 5 pounds and no children under 13 years old.

Miki is a gal that knows what she wants and when she wants it.  Everything in life has to be on her terms because she will try to bite you if she feels she's not in charge of the situation.

She shifts loyalties very easily, and will be a velcro dog to whoever she feels is her person at the time.

That said, she doesn't have any separation anxiety, though that could change from household to household and can be independent if she needs to be.

She hates cats (more scared than anything) is not great with dogs (again, probably more scared as every dog is bigger than her) and has a 3 time bite history with humans.

BUT, this dog is also incredibly sweet and kind and cuddly and loving and if you understand chihuahua's you'll love Miki for who she is as a dog.  

She is still working on housetraining, be it pee pads or going outside, so patience in this area will be important.

We are looking for a quiet home for Miki. Someone that is home more often than not or can take their pet to work.  Someone that is patient and kind.  Someone that understands chihuahua's and all the oddness that is this amazing breed.

FROM HER FOSTER MOM:

Mickey is a tiny cuddler, who likes to be carried around or on your lap. 

She is playful in the afternoons, where she will chase her tail, climb & paw at you, and use her teeth, but very gently. 

She may copy your yoga poses, and I think she thinks yoga is me trying to play with her, so she'll climb you and get right up in your space if you practice yoga/home exercises. 

She really likes her walks and will allow you to bundle her up in a sweater & jacket and get her harness on without much struggle. 

She doesn't bark to go out or give you notice that she needs to go out, so I find routine walks work well for her, especially before bed and first thing in the morning. She has asked to out in the middle of the night several times, only to not go potty, just to enjoy the smells and explore so I'm working on curbing that.

She has a very low appetite, but hopefully you can find the right food for her to eat more enthusiastically as it's still a work in progress. 

She does bark at little noises & shadows inside, and people & dogs on walks, but she is already showing improvement so if you can keep up the positive reinforcement I'm sure it will continue to improve. 

She likes to sleep on the bed, over the covers, curled up in the knook between or behind your legs (depending on how you sleep). 

She's had some accidents inside despite the regular walks and pee pads spread throughout the place, but knows she shouldn't be, and will give you giant puppy dog eyes and maybe even hide in her crate so I'm only rewarding walks where she goes potty now, and trying to encourage regular spots for it. 

She is a pretty typical chihuahua velcro dog, sticks right by your side and is always checking to make sure you're right there, but doesn't seem to experience any separation anxiety when I leave. 

Great little companion who loves to be petted all the time, and is not shy to ask for belly rubs; you can carry her in one arm easily, and find her hiding under a pile of blankets and pillows or up high in a basket when you get home.


____________________________________________

As of today, though our protocols could change tomorrow, we are still moving forward with adoptions. Our process has changed from some of the previous elements: We are a registered animal welfare organization, so we are deemed an essential service.

All paperwork completed online, video home visits, meet and greets outside respecting social distancing, leashes/collars/supplies wiped down and disinfected (GermiCide 3 wipes), disinfectant on the dog prior to handoff (Aqueos wipes for dogs)

-----------------------

To note: the above description is relevant to this dog in his current setting. Home changes & adopter personalities can bring out different behaviours not previously seen.

We do not specifically kid/cat test our dogs when they arrive at Mattie's Place. That just wouldn't be fair to the dog or child/cat.

We also do not claim, endorse, suggest or hint at, that any of our dogs are hypoallergenic, low shed or no-shed.

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, deworming, defleaing, vaccinations, nose to tail health exam, leash|collar, 6 months of preventative based on season/need, DNA test for entertainment purposes, dishes, poop bags, food and any extras she has accumulated in foster care.

animal.description:
Teddy is a handsome, senior Belgian Malinois, roughly 8 years old, and 55 lbs. He is UTD on his vaccinations, heartworm negative, and is neutered. Being the older gentleman that he is, he does experience some sore hips so he needs some TLC with supplements and understanding. Teddy LOVES playing ball. He wil chase it for hours (see previous sentence). He forgets that he's not a pup anymore! He likes to play with other dogs, but is not a fan of small dogs, cats, or squirrels. In his mind, those little critters are for chasing! We are currently unsure on how he is with kids, but we'll update as we know more about him. He only just arrived at his foster home, so we look forward to seeing him settle. 

Teddy loves to snuggle and be with his people. We are not sure how much experience he has with living in a house as he tries to mark indoors. His foster is working with him to correct it, so we can soon say he'll be fully "housebroken". He just needs to learn the house rules. Teddy has had some formal training in his time. He knows all of his basic commands. He is also very food motivated, so this can serve as a great motivator and training tool for him. He stole his transporter's Egg McMuffin on the ride to his foster home!!! What a goof! Teddy does well in the car and enjoys coming along. 

When Teddy came to MAD Rescue, he was a bit underweight, so he will need to put a few pounds on to reach his optimal, healthy weight. If you are looking for a sweet, senior Mal, this is your guy!

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
KANE BROWN is a unique mix of a blue Doberman Pincher, Cane Corso and American Staffordshire Bull Terrier. He is a BIG puppy at just 18 months old, currently 75 lbs and very tall. He loves people and does the 'doberman lean' on his foster Grandpa during play breaks. Kane has a thick beautiful short haired coat requiring no special grooming. Kane loves kids, he knows to sit and give his paw ("high five") when he meets new people but also tries to give hugs. 

 

 

He has been observed to be good with dogs of all sizes - he plays nicely when running with little puppies and other large breed dogs. Due to his age and size, he needs regular exercise and continued leash training. He gets anxious on car rides, he whines and tries to sit with his humans in the front seat. Kane is a social boy who needs to be part of a family and given a 'job' besides being a constant shadow. 

 

Kane will be a great addition to any home, he is affectionate and concerned about all those around him. He would be just as happy in the city or country, as long as people are close by. This handsome boy deserves a forever home to match his loyalty and BIG HEART.

 

 

The adoption fee is $600.00 He is up to date on vaccines according to age, has received proper deworming, and comes with additional dewormer if needed. This pet is microchipped, neutered, comes with 6 months of Heartworm preventative via ProHeart 6 Injection, and one month free trial of pet insurance if registered by adopter with insurance company. All animals receive a health certificate (stating that a licensed veterinarian saw the pet and deemed it healthy for travel, but is not a promise of perfect health.) Our transports are USDA certified and the cost of transport is included in adoption fee!

 

He is currently fostered in Houston, Tx but will be traveling to the PNW on 02/06/2021.

 

Due to the Covid-19 crisis we are experiencing a dramatic influx in inquiries and adoption applications. If you have questions regarding a pup you are interested in please fill out an adoption application. Once received it can take up to a week to complete our review. Be assured we have received your received your application! If you need more information regarding a pup you are interested in, the process of filling out an adoption application is still required prior to answering detailed questions. We value our potential adopters time and appreciate your patience as our staff navigate through the blessing of an overwhelming response for adoptions.

 

Please inquire by submitting an application:

 https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/30255/generic

 

Thank you for your interest in adopting a rescue! 

Kane's Adoption Coordinator - Leah@threelittlepittiesrescue.org

 

Please go to our website to see more about our rescue and what we do! We are very proud of our hard work in saving as many animals as we can, giving them what they need, and matching them with the right families.

animal.description:
Koda had been bounced around a bit in his short life. Relinquished at 7 months, adopted, and passed on through Nextdoor; he had been in 4 homes by the time he was 10 months. The inconsistencies in his life had led him to make independent decisions as smart shepherds are prone to do. He ended up with a fantastic advocate he met through his doggie daycare, who acted as a matchmaker between his last family and us. 

Koda's been getting love, consistent structure, and guidance in his shepherd experienced foster home. He'd been looking for direction on how to be his best self; his foster family has set him in the right path. Although Koda had lived with kids and loved them in his last home, we prefer to place him into a home without young kids. He had developed protective instincts around his favorite folks without appropriate re-direction before coming to us. 

Dog friendly, Koda had regularly attended doggie daycare and is living with dogs in his foster home. He plays happily with friendly dogs outside of his foster home, slightly intimidated by pushy dogs. Koda is super sweet, smart, happy to meet new people. He's been out and about with his people enjoying life thoroughly. 

Koda attaches to his person readily, wanting to please and generous with his cuddles and kisses. Integrated into his foster household, Koda has learned to rely on more than one person for direction and love. He loves toys, bully sticks, and treats. 

Car rides are fun adventures for him, settling in the back seat with his head on the middle console. Weighing in around 55 lbs, he's got a little of another breed to add to his handsome look, maybe a heeler. We love the white tip at the end of his tail. 

Since he's way too interested in chickens and rabbits, we'd say no small critters in Koda's furever home also. 

Given his prior history, we will require adopters interested in Koda to have experience raising adolescent shepherds and a firm commitment to on-going training to work this boy's mind and continue moving forward as a delightful adult.

animal.description:
****UNDER REVIEW*****

This adorable MatchDog has received many applications. Our MatchMakers are currently reviewing all of the apps to find them the best furever home. We are not accepting additional applications at this time.

If you love decadent, delicious, and delightful desserts, then MatchDog has your dish! Introducing the Cutie Pie Pups - chock full of fluffy morsels. 

Meet Cobbler, a 2 year old male Bouvier/Terrier blend WEIGHING 45 POUNDS. Named for the dessert, Cobbler is a warm, comforting bowl of deliciousness that is great any time of day--our Cobbler is the same! He is a beautiful boy with soulful eyes and a fuzzy face. He has a calm disposition, loves head and belly rubs, rarely barks and sleeps all night in his bed. Cobbler is completely housetrained, and can be trusted to be out of his crate when left alone in the house. He loves to run, play and explore his outdoor world. Cobbler has started learning basic commands and will continue to excel with more training...he is a smart boy. Cobbler does well with a calm household and will flourish with love. If you like warm, fuzzy, beautiful desserts that make you happy, consider Cobbler...he is one sweet treat!!

If you think you are a perfect match for Cobbler please complete an application fully: https://www.petstablished.com/organization/243592

Cobbler has been fully vetted, is up to date on all vaccinations and on preventatives for heartworm, flea, and tick. We cannot guarantee breed information. You will find price guidelines for adoption at matchdogrescue.org and you can read about the whole adoption process and what MatchDog Rescue provides with each dog

This gorgeous MatchDog is currently being fostered and cared for at our own facility so as to look and feel their best when they meet you .

If you see a pending notification on this dog, it means we have informed the lucky family selected as the best match for this particular dog and they have agreed to come to the transport/event with the goal of taking the dog to their forever home. If for any reason this plan falls through, we will change the picture back to its original format and revisit other applications.

animal.description:
*Due to concerns surrounding COVID-19, we have reformatted the way that we do adoptions in order to follow social distancing protocols. We are thrilled that so many people want to adopt right now, but we are not equipped to handle the large number of calls, applications, and email inquiries we are receiving. We are no longer answering phone calls and are doing all communications with adopters via email. If you have a dog you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application before sending us emails. When your application has been processed, you will receive an email from us with further instructions on how to adopt. You do not need a new application for every dog that you are interested in adopting. 

At MAMCO we understand that in order to continue rescuing moms and babies, we must stretch our finances as far as we are able. For this reason we use variable adoption pricing. By assigning higher adoption fees to high demand moms and puppies, we are able to rescue more families in need.The money raised through these adoptions acts as a benefactor to moms and puppies in our care who require expensive veterinary treatments, have behavioral issues, or need more time to find a home. We often reduce the adoption fees on these harder-to-place moms and puppies to help them find forever families. Adoption fees vary, but all include spay or neuter, microchip, up to date vaccinations and deworming, rabies vaccine at the time of spay or neuter, and 30 days of pet insurance. We also cover hernia repair and cherry eye repair at the time of spay or neuter. Applications can be filled out at mamcorescue.org.

Kando is a really sweet dog. He does fine with dogs his size, but bigger dogs seem to scare him a little bit. His appetite hasn't been like other dogs and he won't eat the dog food I offered him. The only thing he has been eating is mostly bacon treats and pepperoni treat sticks, he seems to favor wet food. He loves all humans big and small, and trusts them.

HW+ simply means the dog has tested positive for heart worms in our screening process. We utilize what is called the fast-kill method which means we place the dog on antibiotics for 30 days and then administer 3 injections in increments afterward. The cost to treat heart worms is rather steep. However, thanks to our generous donors, we are able to cover that cost for our adopters so long as they go to our veterinarian, Red Rocks Animal Center in Lakewood.

animal.description:
Faye has come a long way in just 4 days so we hope that whoever fosters her can be patient and allow her a few days to come out of her shell. Here are a few thoughts and photos we hope will help her to find a new foster or better yet a forever family. When Faye first came to us she was carried out of the shelter and the poor girl was shaking like a leaf. When we got home we backed the car into the garage and opened up the tailgate. She stayed in the back of the car for about an hour without moving. We had hoped she would come out of her own accord but in the end, we had to lift her out and carry her into the house. She did eat with no problem except she seemed to prefer to wait until we were out of sight. She actually has a good appetite but did prefer her dry food mixed with some canned dog food. She spent most of the first day in the crate. The next day we encouraged her to walk through the house on the leash. On day four she walked through the house to go outside where she sat enjoying the warmth and we left her alone but left the back door open. Her last day with us - she came out of her crate this morning with no encouragement while wagging her tail. Faye took herself to the backyard where she had wandered about and rolled in the grass all the while wagging her tail and appearing much happier. One thing that did surprise us is that she has the ability to go a long time without going outside yet no "accidents" in the house. Faye is a gentle girl - she has taken treats - and hotdogs - from our hand very gently. Although she was clearly afraid when we picked her up at no time did she snarl or snap at us. On her last day with us she found her voice. She didn't bark but when she walked out of her crate this morning wagging her tail with a big smile on her face she made funny little noises as if she was trying to talk to us. Later, when she was outside enjoying the fine weather she would come to the open back door and talk to us while wagging her tail as if to say aren't you going to come out to play? It is clear that she has been through a lot and almost seems depressed. We feel that a quiet place where she has time to come around at her own pace and feel safe and secure would be best for her. Too much noise and stimulation may frighten her. Our house is very quiet with just the two of us and we have left her to come around at her own pace and it seems to have worked. Faye obviously has a sad story and we almost wish she could tell us what happened to her so we could help her better. I am sure she will find her place within the right home and I am happy for any future foster or adopter to contact me if I can help in any way. I would love to follow her progress and given a few months I am sure she will be a completely different girl than the sad, shaking girl we collected from the shelter. 

Faye had belonged to a truck driver; when she was younger, she spent a lot of time riding with him, but once she got older, he had to leave her at home more frequently. While he was on the road, he would leave Faye with his mother. Unfortunately, after a long trip on the road, he came back to a pregnant Faye. He thought he might be able to care for them, but with his mom's older age and him being gone so frequently, he knew this family would not get the care that they needed. So he took them to the shelter, hoping to be able to give them all a better life than he could provide them. Faye is incredibly fearful in the shelter as you'll see in the video. She just needs a soft place to fall where she can decompress and come out of her shell.

We have no back story or update for this dog at this time. When we do, it will be updated here. This is all the information we have currently.

animal.description: Please meet Star. Star is a 4-5 month old very sweet hound possibly lab or other large breed mix puppy who loves to cuddle and meet new people. Doing very well with house breaking and working hard on leash training. Cars, loud noises, and barking dogs scare her a little so she would do best in home with a fenced in yard. Star loves to run and play outside and would probably do well with another dog to play with, but a meet and greet would be necessary. Star is now spayed, up to date with vaccines for her age and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $450.00. If you are interested in adopting Star, please visit our website www.LHARinc.org go to Adopt and complete the dog adoption application.

Please read the dog's entire bio before you apply.  Sadly, we are no longer able to respond to every application, but will contact the one that is a good match within 3 days.
Holly is a female 4 yr old maltipo (born 11/5/2016), really more poodle then anything.   She is sweet and social and tons of fun.  Holly is 12-13 lbs and so very cute.  She does not love being alone and has lived with another dog.  Holly had a bladder stone, which had to be removed surgically, so whoever adopts her has to undestand that she will need to be on prescription food with regular exams for the rest of her life, no exceptions as otherwise she will make more stones and that is painful and very expensive.  She loves walks and can handle really long ones.  Holly has good housemanners and is a joy to have in the home.   She is a bit too much for kitties.   Holly is crate trained and goes right into her crate for travel.
Most of our dogs are not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up.  If you do not live within a 2 hr drive of Orange County, please email us before applying to see if the dog you are interested is may be a candidate for long distance adoption.    We only make consider long distance adoptions for dogs who have been in our rescue for 6 plus months with no local candidates.
If you are interested in adopting one of our rescues, please visit our main website for adoption procedures at www.pupsandpals.net and then fill out our application.  Please note that we are all volunteers so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us if your application is a good match for the pet. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated, microchipped, and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Listed for adoption: 1/18/2021
Adoption fee: $350
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.

We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated, microchipped, and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Listed for adoption:  1/18/2021
Adoption fee: $300
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

animal.description:
Bruce is differently-abled due to all four of his legs having congenital abnormalities. Bruce was found wondering the streets and was very malnourished. He's now happy and healthy! Bruce is a quirky little dude, he overall prefers the people he lives with and can be very standoffish with new people, he does become defensive when new people enter his home or yard. Bruce needs a low traffic home and would love someone who is home frequently. He also needs someone very experienced in dog behavior and who will understand and respect his behavioral needs. 

Bruce does really good with other dogs but overall prefers snuggles with humans. He's good with cats as well! Bruce does not need to be in a home with small kids he would however be fine with older kids. 

Bruce spends most of his time sleeping, if you're chilling then he's chilling. He does get the cutest happy dance and bounce when he's excited. Bruce absolutely loves treats, especially dental treats! Bruce likes to pee when he wants to pee and wears a belly band inside. Bruce rarely poops inside unless you leave him alone for too long, then he'll poop and smash it everywhere. Bruce loves loves to be outside and will soak up all the sunshine but he also really loves to be inside too. 

Our little man is only available for foster to adopt so we can ensure the best quality fit for him! If interested please contact our director at krfdirector@kanoarescuefoundation.org or send her a text at (405)255-3484.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Bruce has been around small critters and seems to do really well!

animal.description:
Draco was recently placed and returned because he was too much for the resident Chihuahua.  And while it wasn't the right match, it is no reflection on this dude!  When I first met him I thought he would be a handful, but honestly I found him to be quite a sweet dog.  No edges.  He is all puppy and needs manners (he jumped up on top of the picnic table and loves to be on top of his kennel dog house) but manners are easy to teach.  Temperament is what is really important and Draco's is just wonderful.

Are you looking for young and fun without having to deal with all the hassles that come with a young puppy?  If so, then Draco might be the right match for you!  At just 9 months old and about 45 pounds he is every bit a puppy, but housebroken and having some basic manners already established (he will sit on command for a treat).   

Of course don't let that fool you, he still has ALL the energy of a young dog so his new family must be ready to give him plenty of exercise.  Lots of walks, runs and fetch in the yard will be needed.    Draco is good on leash, pulling just a little but corrects every easily. 

Draco is housebroken and crate trained (although it will need to be a very solid and sturdy crate as he can break out of a cheap crate).  We have found that he will even hold it in his kennel at the shelter which is amazing!  He is good with other dogs and seems to be good with cats.  

While Draco is good with kids, his previous owner said that he is too much of a large puppy to be placed with small children.  All the screaming and running gets him excited and he wants to join the fun and that can get overwhelming.  So children over 10 would be recommended.

PLEASE NOTE:    DO NOT CALL THE SHELTER.  If you have questions you will get a much faster response if you email questions to  HSPCdogs@gmail.com  
 
We are open for adoptions Thursday - Saturday from 12-4pm (excluding holidays).  Adoptions are on a first come, first serve basis.  Adoption fee is $100 (cash or check only, NO credit cards).   Meet and greets with kids and other dogs are required.

animal.description:
COCO WILL BE AVAILABLE ONCE SHE IS SPAY AND HAS RECOVERED. OUR VET IS SCHEDULING SPAYS NOW FOR MID/END OF JANUARY. Although her foster says she does well with other dogs, she is at the age when this could change drastically. Any adopter should use the usual precautions in introducing her to other dogs.
From her foster:
Coco does really well with other dogs. Coco lives with one male husky and is able to go to the local dog park and socially interact with other dogs and people. She's also been interactive with children of the ages of 5 and 10. Coco is housebroken. She understands some commands like sit and paw with treats. Is a very smart girl and learning quick. I have only been working with her for a few days and she's been doing great. She is working on walking on the lead, she doesnt pull it just that she walks all over the place. She prefers to be outside running around in a fenced backyard than inside so would recommend someone with a fenced yard. Not possessives of food or toys because she shares everything with the husky at home and with others at the park. She still needs a little help getting up and downstairs she's afraid of them but able to overcome it with some help.This is also a problem when getting her into cars but once she's in the car she just sits and looks out the window. She has been on road trips for hours with ease once in the car

Hi I'm Emmett. I'm the sweetest boy filled with tons of kisses. I love chasing balls and playing tug with my human foster siblings. Squeaky toys are simply amazing to Emmet. He also enjoys a good snuggle in his foster moms lap. Emmet will make an amazing addition to a family . After all who wouldn't want to play with this handsome boy. Emmet is estimated to be 11 weeks old and 9 lbs. Since we don't know at all what doggy genes are in the dog's make up (we don't know who mom and dad are!), we are just guessing on breed and size when grown. 

All dogs have had a vet exam, are up to date on vaccinations, have been given a dewormer, treated for fleas and given heartworm preventative.  Dogs over 7 months have been heartworm tested.  

Please note that because we require a home visit at the time of adoption we can only place animals in homes within a 60 mile radius of Minneapolis. If you are interested in meeting this dog please fill out the pre-adoption application on our website at http://www.safehandsrescue.org under Adopt and we will get back to you to arrange a meeting in the foster home.

Meet King! This 3 year-old mush is an expert at sit and loves to play ball. He was surrendered when his owners moved and couldn’t take him with them. He has been terrified at the shelter and it took 5 days to get him out of his kennel. He has really started to show his personality and he really loves to give kisses even though it still takes him a minute to warm up to new people. We will dog test him tonight, now that he has settled. He is full grown at about 75 lbs. 
CATS: Not tested, no high prey drive observed so far
OTHER DOGS: Yes
KIDS: Yes, but with supervision as he is big and does like to mount  (being neutered soon!)

FOLLOW THESE INSTRUCTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED: 

To adopt, complete the application at tarnj.org/adopt

If you have any questions at all, please DO NOT use the PetFinder inquiry form as we do not respond to those. Questions should be sent to info@tarnj.org. 

An application is required before any meets are scheduled so the best way to be considered is to apply ASAP at tarnj.org/adopt.

We are all volunteer-run and do our best to respond to every application. If there is a match with your application, you should hear from us within 2-5 days. If you do not hear from us, please check your Junk folder or email us for an update.

animal.description:
*PLEASE NOTE: FAMILIES INTERESTED IN THIS LITTER MUST HAVE PRIOR GERMAN SHEPHERD EXPERIENCE & A YARD*

Bandit is a 6 month old neutered male German Shepherd mix who weighs 48 lbs. Bandit and his brothers came to All 4 Paws after their owner passed away and family members could not provide them with the attention they deserved. It was a heartbreaking situation and we are so grateful for the opportunity to help these sweet pups. These boys are going to grow up to be big, loyal companions. They are incredibly intelligent and excel with a job. We are looking for families with direct experience with owning German Shepherds for them, so their families understand their needs from the get go. Activity - both mental and physical - is essential for their well being, and they will thrive in experienced homes. They have always lived with other dogs and have been comfortable with respectful children who do not overwhelm them. Bandit seems to rely on other dogs for comfort so his ideal forever home will have other dogs. He will need a home without cats. Bandit has always had a yard to exercise in and seems most happy when he can be outdoors a lot, so he is looking for a forever home with a yard too. Bandit is very shy at first and needs time to get comfortable. He'll need a patient family with a quieter home in order to feel safe. With some time, dedication, and lots of love we have no doubt Bandit will blossom into a devoted family companion; all he needs is a chance. 

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website:https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more:https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Follow us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets:https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

animal.description:
Reimer came to us after he was found as a stray. Reimer's genitals did not develop correctly causing him to retain a lot of urine, this resulted in him having a penile amputation. Reimer is still not always able to control his bladder, he is on medications that help him out and he has less accidents because of it but he is not always 100%. Reimer absolutely LOVES to play and be around other dogs. Reimer is pretty energetic so we do not suggest a home who wants a lazy dog, he needs a home and family that will keep him active and burn his energy. 

Reimer would do best with older kids, he is a little much for little kids and would most likely knock them over and accidentally hurt him. Reimer thinks he is a small dog and literally does not understand his size so can be rough with little dogs but has never hurt any small dogs, he just tends to play rougher than little dogs prefer. If dogs do not want to play with him then he respects their space!

Reimer does need slow introductions, when we bring people over to meet he stands back for a few seconds but quickly makes friends! He basically just wants to be loved by everyone. Reimer truly is very eager to please, he loves training time!


Our sweet man is only available for foster to adopt as we want to ensure the family adopting him is able to handle him and truly love him for all that he is! Please contact our director directly at krfdirector@kanoarescuefoundation.org you can also text her at (405)255-3484 with any questions regarding Reimer.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Reimer has been around a variety of animals including birds and has done really well.
