Name:  Wall-E
Age:  8
Weight:  15 lbs 
Sex/Spayed or neutered?: Male/Neutered 
Coat: Smooth
Color:  Red
Energy Level:  low
Adoption Fee: $200 
Contact: kyle_knell@yahoo.com

Wall-E is a shy, super sweet, snuggly little Dachshund.  He would be a perfect companion for someone with a laid-back lifestyle.  He was an owner surrender and his vet visits were a bit out of date, but after a couple visits and some dental work done he is completely healthy, all shots up to date, and ready to find his furever family. He gets along with other dogs fine and loves people, even though he can be a little shy at first.  His favorite activity is to curl up on a lap and be spoiled with petting and bellyrubs.  He does alright on a leash, but we jokingly call him the "Poky Little Puppy", he is never in a rush.  He likes casual strolls over fast-paced walks any day.  He hasn't had any behavioral issues while in foster care, and he's well house-trained.  He does not like the crate, but he hasn't caused any trouble outside of it at night or while the family is gone.  This guy is so ready to take up some lap space on someone who loves sunny patches and book reading.  He will have no problem becoming a wonderful, quiet companion.

If you want to help with this dog’s medical expenses: 
https://therescuedrescuers.org/how-to-help

If you want to adopt this dog, apply at the link! 
https://therescuedrescuers.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
I'm a 4 year old mixed breed boy with a friendly personality. I came to the HSJC from Noah's Ark in Texas and am excited to find a loving home in Wisconsin! I have a medium/high energy level and will need daily exercise and play time with my family. I'm a big guy at 56 lbs. who will benefit from obedience training. Did you know obedience training not only teaches dogs good manners, but also helps dogs bond with their new owners? It's true! I am approved for respectful children over the age of 10 and will be a great addition to a caring and involved family. If you can commit to an active and affectionate canine companion, I'd love to meet you! Barkley is approved for families with respectful children over the age of 10.

The online adoption listing websites require that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

animal.description:
Moose
American Bulldog/Mastiff Mix
Male 
3 years old
78 lbs.

Hey friends! I’m Moose and I’m a big guy with a big personality looking for a big love with my forever family. If you’re up for super-sized fun and affection, read on for more about me!

I’m a happy guy who spends a lot of time smiling, loves my people and bonds to them quickly. Sometimes I forget how big I am and try to crawl up in my foster dad’s lap for snuggles. I’m such a fun “work from home” companion and mostly just lay by your feet and keep you company (but once in a while, I’ll nuzzle in for some love throughout the day!) Not to brag, but I tend to win over the hearts of everyone I meet with my goofy and quirky personality!

My favorite place to be is napping with my people but every so often I do get the zoomies and like to take off, running and playing. I love playing tug with my rope toy and fetching balls and sticks. My foster dad says it’s pretty funny watching a big guy like me zoom around. 

I do struggle with politely meeting new dogs on and off leash and I am STRONG  so I need to be the only dog in the home. I also need an adopter who can help me avoid meeting dogs on walks and is willing to help me learn to be more relaxed when I see dogs overall. I’ve been working with a trainer and have made lots of progress. I’m SO eager to learn and just need a human to help me thrive! Due to this, I won’t be a candidate for an apartment living situation and it’s very important that I have a 6ft fence in the entire backyard. I also have some reactivity to men who come into my house without a proper introduction so I need a home where someone either doesn’t have a ton of visitors coming over or someone who can just let me meet a male visitor properly first. I am WONDERFUL with men in general-just a random visitor who walks in the door can be overwhelming to me. 

I’m overall a happy, playful, cuddly guy who just wants to love. I will be such an awesome companion! If you’d like to learn more about me, please visit PawsCo’s website at www.pawsco.org to fill out an application or email adopt@pawscoadoptions.org for more information about me!

animal.description:
Hello, world! I'm Ella, and I'm looking for my forever family to have adventures with! I was born in late October and am 15 pounds lab mix who will be a medium/large dog when fully grown. I spend my days alternating between wrestling and running all over the backyard with the other puppy and dog I live with and cuddling for naps. I also live with two cats, but they don't like to play so I ignore them. They're no fun. But you know what's fun? Playing tug of war! And getting treats! I like getting treats so I am a fast learner when it comes to commands. I am starting to get the hang of this potty training too but I still have accidents sometimes. My foster mom says that's okay and we keep trying. She says I'm a good girl full of curiosity and love. When she opens the gate to our doggy room in the morning after I sleep all night long, the first thing I want is cuddles and then to go explore and play. 

My previous owners gave me and my siblings up so now I am looking for a new family who likes to play and give snuggles. I'd be really great in a house with kids and other dogs so I have playmates. I’m dewormed, microchipped, UTD on vaccines, and looking for my forever home! Is it with your family? Meet me and find out!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
Meet Maya! This Samoyed mixed beauty is very smart and will be eager to continue learning.

Maya is a very affectionate dog who loves to run and play. She is a very active 8 year old and does not show signs of slowing down. Like most of her breed, she is a little stubborn and will need someone who is familiar with her breed and knows how to work with them.

She enjoys walks but needs work on the leash. She likes to bark at her surroundings a bit - squirrels, cars etc catch her interest. She loves playing in the yard and needs a secure fence.

She cannot be around chickens, cats, squirrels, small critters, and farm animals.

Maya will be good for families with kids over 12. She has a lot of energy and can be a little mouthy when she feels very playful.

She likes her folks to be around more often than not. Loves her people.

She is now updated on all shots, spayed and chipped. Her adoption fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
RUS BARNWELL was found as a stray by a local GA woman. He was emaciated and covered in fleas. She took him in and cared for him until there was room for him at the local shelter. Rus is a 6+ year old handsome bully mix with so much love to give! He is good with other dogs and children too! If he goes to a home with children, they should be older children (8+ yrs). Rus can get excited and accidently knock down small children. Rus loves to play with his toys and clown around with other dogs. He seems to be ok with cats, but definitely wants to chase them. Rus walks pretty well on leash too! He's a smart boy and knows the sit command. Check out his videos on this page from when he was in the shelter and now that he's at our rescue. Rus would make a great addition to any family!

Apply to adopt RUS BARNWELL at EHRDOGS.ORG and be sure to mention him by name!!

animal.description:
Meet Azul.

Azul is an 8 year old spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, heartworm negative  Staffordshire terrier mix female. 

She has been with the same family since she was a puppy, and she and her brother Django were given up to a relative when her owner recently had a baby.

She is playful and high energy for her age, very loving to all people, but has not had exposure to other dogs besides her brother. Therefore, she needs a home where she will be the only dog and get all of the doggo attention and love.

—————————————

All PETronus Rescue dogs receive basic vaccinations (distemper/parvo, bordetella, & rabies), spay/ neuter, and microchip prior to adoption. We also treat any know medical issues, including heartworms.

Our dogs live in foster homes while they wait patiently for their forever families to find them. This is beneficial in that they learn house manners, crate training, housebreaking, etc while they wait and we are also able to get a very realistic picture of their energy level, temperament, etc so that we can place them in a home that is the best fit.

Our adoption fees are $200 for dogs over 1 year of age and $250 for dogs under 1 year of age. Puppies receive 3 rounds of puppy vaccinations.

If you are interested in adopting one of our amazing dogs, please fill out our adoption application here http://bit.ly/PRAdoption and we will be in touch!

animal.description:
Bear is looking for an experienced owner who can provide him with a quiet, low key home and a consistent daily routine.  Bear would fit best in a home as the only dog with children 16 yo+.
Some of Bear’s favorite things are going for short walks (ideally a few times a day), long naps, spending time outside taking in the fresh air, getting brushed, going for car rides, belly rubs and laying at his person’s feet.  
Bear is considered to be low energy, however if you want to see the puppy in Bear come out, mention the word “walk” and get your boots and coat on!  He is a pro at walking nicely on a leash and loves going on short, slow strolls and taking in all the scents he can!  
Bear is house trained and crate trained.  He needs a home that will be consistent in keeping up his crate routine during the day and most importantly at night.  Bear will thrive in a home with an owner that is able to respect that sometimes Bear likes to have quiet time and space.  Bear can be protective of his “person” and doesn’t always like to share attention.  Bear likes to take a slow and steady approach to eating and likes to have his space while eating.

Bear is more than ready to be someone’s best friend and part of a forever family! Could that be you?

Bear’s adoption fee is $250. That includes the cost of spaying, up to date vaccinations, foster care, rescue, and transport fees. 

To get the ball rolling, head over to our Adoption Application and submit your application today. 

A Dog Bear representative will contact you within 24 hours. 

To help speed up the process contact your vet and give them permission to speak with us. 

If you do not get a response within 24 hours of submitting your application, please check your spam folder.

animal.description: Cookie is around 9 months old, born 4/26/2020.  She is a very little girl weighing in at about 3 1/2 pounds.  She will always be a tiny little girl.  She is fun and social.  Dog friendly, cat friendly.  We are looking for a home with NO small children and NO large dogs, NO exceptions.  We require this due to her small size and being injured by kids or other dogs.  Cookie is being released by her owner due to a possible medical condition.  Cookies new owner must be financially secure, own their own home and able to cover any medical expenses for her if ever needed.  Be prepared to prove you can do this.  We are looking for someone wealthy enough who will not need to depend on pet insurance if a medical necessity happens.  More will be explained in person.  Cookies owner must keep her well socialized.  Due to her breed, purebred toy poodle, she will require being taken to a groomer about every 4 to 5 weeks.  The rescue also requires the future owner to have a car seat for her while in a vehicle.  If you think you fit these requirements contact the rescue at suzzie38@gmail.com.  Home visits and a contract are mandatory, no exceptions.  We are not doing out of state adoptions at this time. You must be in Pennsylvania and within 75 miles of 17257.  Thanks, have a great day!

animal.description:
*PLEASE NOTE:  We do not adopt out on a first-come/first-serve basis.  Applications are accepted for a puppy and then a home check is scheduled.  If there are multiple applications for a puppy, after all home checks are done, then the puppy is adopted out to the home that is the best fit for that puppy.
***** All breeds listed are a best guess or based on information from our rescue partners and are not guaranteed*****
 
 ******Chicagoland Dog Rescue reserves the right to restrict adoption of a dog to potential adopters who live within a fifty (50) mile radius of Schaumburg, IL *****

Hi! My name is Charlotte and if you are looking for a dog who wants to hang with you…it's ME! I am very affectionate and love to follow my foster Mom everywhere! I do have a furry foster brother and he and I have the best time running around out in the yard. I do have lots of puppy energy but also love a good nap, hopefully on my foster Mom’s lap! I have not quite mastered the whole walking on a leash thing yet but I am a smart girl so I know that with time, I will get the hang of it! And being such a smart girl I do have sit down pat, especially when a treat is involved! I am working on potty and crate training and doing well with both. I just know that with lots of love, training, and patience, I will be one GREAT dog! If you would like to meet me, please fill out a pre-adoption application and a CDR volunteer will get back to you just as quick as they can!
Snuggles and kisses-Charlotte


**The ADOPTION FEE for this pet is $450 which includes getting the puppy/dog up to date on rabies, distemper and bordetella vaccines, fecal test and deworming if necessary, heartworm test, spay or neuter (not including pre-surgical bloodwork) and a microchip. Free access to our weekly training classes is also included for the life of the dog, something no other rescue in the area offers.***

Snowball was owner surrendered. His owners were not caring for him and he was a matted mess. As a result he was hurting and biting at them.

Snowball has been a loving dog since he was groomed and the tangles were removed. He had some sores, which are healing. He was also covered in fleas, which we have treated.

Snowball needs a loving family that is going to treat him with love and understanding. He is afraid of men, which makes us wonder how he was being treated. The lady that turned him in said he was running with their other 15 to 20 dogs outside. He needs work on potty training, since he never lived inside. Once he bonds with you, he is 120% yours. He follows his foster mom everywhere. He is wanting a connection with a family. But he takes a day to warm up and he is a fear biter if you try to rush him.

A LITTLE BIT ABOUT ME! 
1/11/21: HELLO, MY NAME IS SAM. I AM ABOUT 8 YEARS OLD AND WOULD LOVE TO FIND A FOREVER HOME  WITH A FENCE AND KIDDOS AND OTHER DOGS IF POSSIBLE. I LOVE TO CUDDLE UP NEXT TO YOU ON A SOFA AND IN BED SO HOPING SOMEONE WILL ALLOW ME TO DO THIS ONCE ADOPTED.

I WAS IN A FOSTER HOME WITH A SMALL CHILDREN, DOGS, AND CATS AND DID GREAT.

I AM ALSO HOUSETRAINED, DO WELL IN A CAR AND  HAVE ALL OF  VET WORK DONE INCLUDING NEUTERING MICROCHIPPED,  AND ON MONTHLY PREVENTION,AND ALL SHOTS UP TO DATE. 

PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ME AND I HOPE TO MEET YOU SOON!

HERE IS SOME MORE YOU NEED TO KNOW IF INTERESTED IN ADOPTING ME! 
Please email Kim at ghogrescue@gmail.com for an application. GRACIE'S HEART OF GOLD ADOPTION APPLICATION GRACIE'S HEART OF GOLD REQUIRES ONGOING PROPER VETERINARY CARE FOR ALL ANIMALS ADOPTED TO INCLUDE HEARTWORM MEDICATIONS, FLEA MEDICATIONS, AND YEARLY VACCINATIONS. GRACIES HEART OF GOLD DOES NOT SHIP OUR DOGS - WE REQUIRE A FACE TO FACE MEETING. WE ALSO DO NOT ADOPT OUR DOGS AS GIFTS UNLESS THE RECIPIENT MEETS WITH THE DOG PRIOR TO ADOPTION. MY ADOPTION FEE IS: $250. THESE FEES HELP KEEP THE RESCUE GOING. PLEASE READ MORE! Adoption fees average $150-$400. This fee varies per animal based on additional vet care required to save them. Due to the rising costs of veterinary care, premium holistic dog food, gasoline prices, and boarding fees, which are paid for out of our own pockets, we recently were forced to raise our fees. We are not funded by anyone - adoption fees help to offset only a part of our cost of getting the dog ready for adoption. All dogs > 6 months are vetted, up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested, wormed and have a goody starter bag. Puppies

Holly is an 12 week old female pit bull mix puppy who weighs about 10 lbs. Holly and her siblings were part of an unplanned litter, and their owner was unable to give them the care they deserved. We feel lucky to have had the opportunity to save these cuties and find them wonderful families that will love and care for them forever! They have been in a wonderful foster home since the day they were born, so they are very friendly and social. Holly is last of her litter to find her forever home, and she is looking for a special one. This little girl is super smart and eager to please. She's doing great with her house and crate training, and will work for treats. She will need a family who has experience with strong-willed breeds as she is a little sassy about being handled sometimes. She is affectionate though when it is on her terms and will cuddle up in your lap for a nap. Holly is a little weary of new people, but warms up once given some time. She loves to play and chew on her toys. Holly is pretty obsessed with her canine foster sister and is learning a lot from her. We are requiring her forever home have a confident canine pal to help teach her the ropes. With love and patience we have no doubt this beautiful girl will grow up into a loyal and loving companion, all she needs is a chance. Please help us find Holly the forever home she's been dreaming of!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website:https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more:https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Follow us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets:https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

animal.description:
***REQUIRES A FENCED IN YARD***

Everyone give a big nose boop to Sammie girl! Sammie is a 20-month-old merle labradane girl who is the definition of AFFECTIONATE, HAPPY and ENERGETIC! 

She is currently living with two toy breed dogs and kids and doing great. She previously lived with bully mixes and loves the dog park too, she's great with other dogs. BUT she is HYPER!! She's a very active girl, she LOVES to play ball, and she can be a bit overwhelming for senior dogs or any dog that isn't a fan of lots of playful energy.

We still need to get her spayed and settled into foster care so we can learn about her needs. We know this much: She is very much a puppy! Nothing gets her down... she has lots and lots (and lots) of energy! She will certainly benefit from a large playmate. She is rock solid with kiddos.

Sammie's adoption fee is $300. To apply for Sammie please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt. After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email PlusDogs@ILDobeRescue.com. Our adoption radius is 3 hours from the Chicagoland area.

Diamond is an adorable 2-year-old Chihuahua/Pug-mix, who was surrendered to animal control and transferred to IDR+ with no background. Her foster home has learned a lot about her over the past few months and wants to find her a great match! She is completely crate-trained and housebroken, but watch for her to sit at the door as her signal to go out. Diamond currently cohabitates with other smaller and larger dogs and gets along with them, but she gets a little jealous at times. She’d prefer living with a very laid back smaller dog who gives in easily, and she’d even thrive as an only dog. She isn’t a big fan of cuddling with people, but she loves to snuggle with the resident cat! Diamond tolerates the grandkids when they visit, but she doesn’t like when they try to pick her up. She’d be okay with older kids who are respectful of little dogs and know they aren’t toys. She can also be inappropriate with her mouthiness, but her foster mom says “no nibbling–kisses only!” Diamond is very food motivated, so training will be fun! Positive training is always highly recommended to help bond and communicate. She can be leash walked, but her foster mom would like to see her adopted to a home with a fenced yard (no e-fence). Diamond loves to hang out on one of the many dog beds and is endlessly entertained by the selection in the toy bin. She would be a wonderful addition to a household that can keep her mind and body active.

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

animal.description: I AM ON HOLD FOR AN UPCOMING ADOPTION APPOINTMENT Lucus is a handsome 5-year-old mixed-breed fellow who currently weighs about 24 pounds. To meet Lucus or to be added to his waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the DOG'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. If you have other dogs at home, tell the scheduler you would like to bring them along for a Meet n' Greet. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are $50 off for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. She is both crate and housetrained.

animal.description: Callie #7173 is a 13-year-old female Border Collie/Spitz mix. While this older lady can be a bit shy at first, she warms up quickly and is the sweetest soul you could ever meet. She loves to lean against you for comfort, once she knows you. Callie is seeking a nice home to live out her golden years. She has been diagnosed with arthritis and will need to be on joint supplements. She struggles with her vision, but is not completely blind. Callie is a bit finicky with her potty business. While she enjoys going on walks, she prefers to do her business in a fenced-in backyard without the weight of a leash. She is also trained to use pee pads, so having those around the house is a good idea. Callie is good with cats and other dogs that are her size. Dogs that are bigger than her frighten her. She absolutely loves cheese! She weighs 27 pounds and is full grown. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
Sierra is a 5 year young Great Pyrenees and Anatolian Shepherd mix that weighs about 80lbs. Sierra arrived at her foster home on December, 27, 2020. When Sierra arrived, she was a bit shy and not very confident. However, Sierra seems to have adapted quickly and well to her new large fenced in property and the companionship of her foster parents who respect her breed. Sierra loves to be outside with her people. Sierra also loves being in the house and enjoys her couch, chew toys and cuddle time. Sierra loves to be petted and thrives from it. Sierra enjoyed the company of another dog for 10 days at her foster home. She played well with the other dog but she is a large dog and play dates are best supervised as she likes to do butt slams and doesn't realize how strong she is. She is very playful and has a gentle way going about it. Sierra will bark if another dog comes around her property but not aggressively more of a communication that she wishes she could run free and play with the other dog. Sierra has been brought to the groomers with her Foster Dad and did very well during her grooming. The groomer loved her and said she was very well behaved. Sierra's Foster Dad brought her to the Veterinarians and again she did very well with her behavior. The vet tech said she was very well behaved. Sierra seems to love people and tries hard to please. Sierra walks well on a lead but she may do best with a harness fitted for her as squirrels make her want to pull. She does get excited about squirrels and likes to chase them out of her fenced in yard. Sierra is learning that her job is to be respectful of the ducks at her foster home and that protecting them is her job. Sierra doesn't do well with cats. We were warned about this from her previous caregiver. Her foster family has a cat. Sierra will bark at the cat and chase the cat if given the chance. However, Sierra doesn't challenge the gate which the cat is behind. Sierra doesn't challenge the 6' high fencing at her foster home either. Sierra enjoys her quiet times at night and her once a day Greenie dog dental chew. Sierra likes to watch her meals being prepared and enjoys her food. Sierra does not sleep in a crate at her foster home. Sierra sleeps in the master bedroom with her foster dad and will get up and make space for him at bedtime. No guarding her food, bed or toys. Sierra will share her toys and initiate play. Sierra will sit patiently to get her treat, go outside or come in. Sierra will bark at you and sniff her tail if she needs to go out. Sierra is very gentle when giving her food or treats. Sierra is a joy to have around and she would make a great companion for someone who enjoys the outdoors and especially if they have a large fenced in property. If Sierra really likes you, she will give you a hug and sit down next to you and lean into you while giving you a most adoring look of gratitude.

If you are interested in any of our dogs, please complete our online adoption application:

http://www.lifesaverssp.dreamhosters.com/adoption-applicat
/

We will conduct a phone interview, check references and then a home check. This helps us to match a dog with their potential adopter. The adoption fee is $350.00 for adults and $450.00 for puppies under one year which includes spay/neutering, up-to-date age appropriate vaccinations, flea/tick & heartworm preventative and a health certificate. We foster our dogs in homes, not in shelters. This allows us to get to know the dogs temperaments in order to match them to a home. This also allows us to get the dogs ready to live in their forever homes! All dogs coming from the south have been quarantined for two weeks and fully vetted before traveling to New England!

For more info please email Lifesaversapps@outlook.com OR visit our website:

http://www.lifesaverssp.org/ 1/30/21 12:01 PM

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Mirabella joined us from the Tacoma Humane Society in January 2021. She is estimated to be two years and came to us weighing only 42 pounds.

Foster Update: Mirabella is settling in well. She's an energetic and intelligence dog who loves hanging out with people. She was pretty underweight when she arrived and we are working on adding some meat on her bones. She does well with the resident dog, but has some reactivity to dogs on leash (though she's not aggressive). Initially she's very timid and a slow introduction to people and dogs is best. Once she had a time to check out people, she's a complete love bug. Mirabella is still very timid but is gaining confidence daily with the help of her foster mom. She has recently discovered that she loves to play fetch and very quickly learned to drop the ball. She can still be scared of loud noises and bustling actions and we think she would do best in a home with a fenced yard.

animal.description:
Molly is one of the smallest of Slinky's 7 puppies, at 7.4 lbs. Born October 19. Mostly tan with some white and black. She is a loving, gentle, and playful girl. She is not as rowdy as most of her other siblings, and so she would do best in a quieter home.
Their mom Slinky is a 14 lb red dachshund mix. Father is unknown. Pups and mom are named after Toy Story characters. The puppies should grow to 20-30 lbs. Molly will be on the smaller end. The other pups are Bonnie, Molly, Bo Peep, Woody, Jessie, and Hamm. As of Jan 27, Molly is the only one still available. She has just been spayed and is a little woozy right now.
Molly got her super duper home with human sisters Hailey and Kelsey, mom and dad. We are thrilled for everyone. So many excellent apps for the Toy Story pups. We are always rescuing and always have wonderful dogs that we get to know well.
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

animal.description:
Hi Im Yodel! So happy that you stopped to learn more about me. Im originally from Little Rock, Arkansas but came to Kansas City when my old shelter ran out of room. I hope that doesnt make you sad Im feeling so excited to be here and find my people soon!
At just 1.5 years old, I already know quite a few tricks! I know sit, shake, and speak, plus I know to lay down when you point your finger to the floor! Im sure I can learn a lot more tricks along the way if you have treats or toys that youre offering. While I like treats, toys are my favorite Im super motivated to be the best girl if it means having you play fetch with me! I do have a lot of energy and love to run around so I would benefit from a lot of exercise and some additional obedience training so I can exercise my mind! Ive also been working really hard on keeping my kennel clean and have showed signs of being housebroken! While I will need some patience when I find my new home, I do seem to have a head start on learning how to be house broken! The nice volunteers here say I am incredible smart so I know that I can keep working hard to be the best version of myself!
Recently, I had one of the best days ever! I got to go on a field trip with a really nice volunteer. It was so amazing to get a few hours outside of the shelter and get a taste of what life could be like once my furever family finds me. We got to go on a hike which was awesome its so fun to go on adventures. We also went to Home Depot and walked around which was cool! I got to meet some nice people who offered up some pets and said I was really cute it made me feel so special! I also got to go to a bakery where the volunteer shared one of their tasty treats with me. It was SO good! I did well in the car and overall had a blast! I cant wait to see all the other cool places Ill be able to visit once I leave Wayside.
Since I have never had much of my own, I dont need a whole lot in my future home. Just someone to love and someone to love me right back. Because I have never really interacted with dogs before, I will need to be the only dog in the family since Im not sure how much I really enjoy other four-legged animals. But, I definitely want you to know that I have so much fun, love, and joy to share that I will be all you would ever need. I really hope we can meet soon I cant wait to give you all the kisses in exchange for all the pets!
Love,
Yodel
 ...

animal.description:
Life is uncertain, always eat dessertor ADOPT it!!

We are so excited to finally introduce you to the ultimate fun-sized, super special, extra sweet treat that you won't feel guilty indulging in for the rest of furever-please give a heartfelt 'hello' to our girl, BUTTERSCOTCH! At just 15 pounds, she is teeny tiny but oh so mighty! Let's just say her road to Boston Buddies was anything but sweet; Butterscotch came in to the Rancho Cucamonga Shelter as a stray with dry eye, a fractured pelvis, and a luxated left hip. We quickly learned that although Butterscotch was physically broken, her soul was beautifully resilient and strong. She immediately had FHO surgery on her hip to help restore as much mobility as possible, her fractured pelvis was on its way to healing naturally, her dry eye got a little lubricating love with medicated drops, and her arthritis was put at ease with some pain meds. Never once did our little go-getter get down. Butterscotch kept sharing her contagious toothy grin (we're obsessed!), sweet kisses, and so much love with her doctors, our volunteers, and now her foster momma!

Speaking of foster mom, simply put, she's totally smitten. Butterscotch has settled in quite nice; she's totally potty trained, makes the perfect copilot in the car, doesn't mind getting cleaned up in the tub, and is always up for a good quality belly rub. Ready, waiting, and wanting to be besties with any and every one, Butterscotch is kind to all humankind and has them swooning over her in no time (those puppy brown eyes certainly mesmerize)! Speaking of puppy eyes, you may be wondering how old our little bitty beauty isand the answer is, she's somewhere in between! What does that mean?! The Shelter listed her as 2, our routine vet thought she was closer to 8, and our surgeon certainly thought she was 12+ until she saw how perfect her teeth were then she understood why the shelter listed her at 2. So not so simply put, she's extra special, has stumped the vets, and hey-age is just a number, so let's just say she's somewhere in between 2 and 12 (I bet it's the first you've heard that oneus too)! When it comes to other puppy pals, Butterscotch is best suited in a quiet home and prefers a mellow mate that likes to nap, and snuggle, and snooze rather than run around and play. Butterscotch is spayed, fully vaccinated, heart worm and fecal tested (both negative), and microchipped. She will need long-term drops for her dry eye and pain medication to manage her arthritis. Butterscotch hasn't done too much exercise since her hip surgery, but she does go on small walks and is quite the lady on her leash. She isn't too upset about the lack of outdoor activity, our girl is more of a great indoors woman. She makes the sweetest shadow, loves being everywhere her human is, and is happiest curled up snoozing the day away by your side. Butterscotch is ready, waiting, and more than deserving of the perfect person(s) and her happily furever after. How absolutely sweet life will be with BUTTERSCOTCH.

Please fill out an adoption application on our website
www.bostonbuddies.org

Adoption Donation: $300

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.You MUST submit an application at BFPA.org if you are interested in Scottie! Please note that ALL dogs on our website ARE available.

FOSTER COMMENTS:

Meet Scottie a 60 pound, 1 year old, Terrier mix. He's adorable - great colors and a good personality! He is puppy curious and explore everything, seriously, everything! He does great with a consistent schedule and exercise. He is very loyal and just wants your love.

He is shy at meeting new people, but it's been getting better. We meets visitors outside when we walk but he's also met our neighbors and loved the hugs and petting. Scottie has lived with two other dogs in the past so he could join a family with dogs or be the only dog. I have not seen him interact with cats. He is not living with children but because of his size and puppy like behavior at times, he would do best with older children but not young, small kids.

Scottie is a very sweet dog and is quiet for the most part. If he hears strangers or an odd noise, he will sound the alarm appropriately. Scottie is housebroken! During the day he has gone 5 hours with no problems. At night he sleeps in his crate 9-10 hours with no accidents. He is crate trained and he is very happy and comfy in his crate.

Scottie has the typical high puppy energy and behaviors. After we go for a walk and I remove the leash, his puppy runaround play time kicks in! A fenced yard would be a bonus so he can burn off some of the puppy energy, but not necessary with the appropriate amount of walks and play time. I don't have a yard but take long walks 2x day (30 min +) and 3 smaller ones around the block. On walks he tends to want to lead and pull and mouth on the leash, very typical puppy behavior. I have only had him a short time, so proper equipment is helping and he is quite trainable.

Scottie's favorite things to do are to chew on his nylabone, play with ice cubes, prance as he goes on his walks, getting rubbed down with a towel and like all puppies, chew on things. His thing to chew on is material, ie. towels, blankets and toilet paper. He has not tried to chew on any furniture. This chewing is typical puppy behavior and is correctable. Scottie is super smart and has learned several commands in my short time with him. He has learned , sit, stay and no. We are working on, leave it and down.

Scottie was found as a stray and is looking for his forever home. If you are looking for a sweet guy that is going to be your best friend, Scottie may be the pup for you.

EVERY DOG HAS A STORY: Scottie was found as a stray and is now looking for his forever home. Some of the information contained in this biography includes approximations based on our expertise and is not guaranteed. Applicants must live no further than one hour from Cary NC as our dogs must be seen by a BFPA veterinarian for all medical care prior to adoptions being finalized. Our foster guardians deliver dogs to their new homes for adoption trials and we do home visits to finalize all adoptions. We therefore require applicants to live within an hours drive of Cary NC.

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING SCOTTIE? If so, please fill out our dog adoption application by copying and pasting this link in a new browser window: https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/of/f?c=WHMSYCNC

animal.description:
Meet “Mr. Life of the Party” Kori, a 2 year old male Pit Bull/boxer mix.  He has a gorgeous orange brindle coat (looks like a tiger) with white markings. He is a nice medium size weighing 35 pounds and is solid strong muscle.  Kori was pulled from our local shelter where he had been picked up as a stray by Animal Control and down there for several weeks with no one coming to claim him.  Kori is a very energetic, fun-loving dog.  He will need lots of exercising so we think he would do best in a house environment with a fenced in yard.  

He would make a great running/walking partner.  Kori loves to play with his toys and is very social and friendly.  He should do fine with children 12 and older, not young cause he may jump up to say hi and perhaps knock them down.  Kori did well with the dogs he has been behavior tested with.  We have started on his crate training.  Kori is up to date on his vet care, neutered, heartworm negative and is microchipped.  He is on heartworm and flea/tick prevention.  Need some cheering up during these crazy times, then Kori is the one for you!!


All HSWA dogs are either at our Dog Adoption Facility or in foster homes. All dogs require an appointment to meet.  Please call us at 205-554-0011 or email humaneswa@yahoo.com to request an appointment to see the dog/puppy and to check availability.

Visit us on Facebook! www.facebook.com/humaneswa

Our adoption fee is $75.  Read more information on our adoption process at www.humanesocietyofwa.org/howtoadopt.html.  Then, if you feel your home might be the right forever home and you would like to adopt a dog, submit an online adoption application. The online applications may not work on mobile devices. If the online application does not work on your device, look to the right side of the forms page for a downloadable .PDF copy of the application.

animal.description:
Onyx is an adorable/wrinkly 10 week old American Bulldog/Boxer mix! 

If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! Please fill out an adoption application on our website if you are ready to adopt! 

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoption appointments!


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

animal.description:
Meet Ditto! She is a 3-4 yr old, 40 lb Bulldog/Lab mix, looking for a forever home. Ditto is a super sweet, affectionate pup who adores her human friends! She loves to snuggle, and is eager to please. Ditto has been through some training so she knows basic obedience skills. She is an active pup and would make a wonderful adventure companion for any lucky person! Ditto loves to get all of the attention from her humans, so she prefers to be the only pet in the home. She has so much love to give!! Ditto is house trained, spayed and up to date on vaccines. If this precious pup sounds like the perfect fit for you, email us at lasthoperescuefl@gmail.com! 

*THIS IS A COURTESY POST. This means this pet is not in our rescue. We are assisting with finding this pet a new home, in efforts to keep him/her out of the shelter! We do require an adoption application for courtesy posts, to help find the best match for the animal, in hopes that their new home will be FOREVER!*

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Louie is a sweet 2-year-old Great Pyrenees who hails from rural VA. Louie is your typical Great Pyrenees who loves being outside and is very loyal and protective. He needs a home with a fenced in backyard (with at least a 4' fence) because this big boy has been known to be able to jump quite high. He's a super goofy boy but will need someone who understands his breed and is able to work with him on proper positive training to overcome some resource guarding (very common with the breed).

 Apply to adopt Louie today!

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center

The adoption fee for this dog is $0. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide a free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Please note:  Rokey is being fostered in Iowa.  RAGOM's policy is that all family members along with resident dogs must travel to a foster's home if selected.

Please note, RAGOM's adoption territory includes Minnesota, Iowa, North and South Dakota, and western Wisconsin within 75 miles of the MN border.   At this time, we do not adopt out of our territory.  

Rokey is truly a wonderful companion and a very bright and loving Goldendoodle. He is almost 6 years old, weighs 75 pounds and is bouncy, energetic, and extremely affectionate. He's the kind of dog that follows you around the house, waits for you outside a closed door, and does everything he can to keep you in his sights.

Rokey was lovingly returned to RAGOM by his original adopter who needed to take care of a family member and was no longer able to provide the care that he needs.  He was born with megaesophagus and very simply, that means that the muscles in his throat do not move the food to his stomach.

He eats his meals sitting upright in a special chair that allows gravity to do what his muscles can't.  He is fed regular kibble with water added so that it's a soupy mix—he loves this stuff!  He is fed in his special chair and then he stays in the chair for about 20 minutes after each meal. He really wants a person there with him to keep him company.

He likes to be petted and sometimes the foster will do some simple combing of his fur while he's in the chair. After his upright time, he spends some quiet time in the house for a bit and then he's playing with the dogs, going for rides, and enjoying the regular routine.

If he's in the house, the fosters typically have him wear a pillow collar that keeps his head up. He knows all about this and wears it without problem. The goal is to get him to twice-a-day feedings, but right now three meals seems to work best for our household routine.

He is a tall boy who really enjoys playing with the foster's resident dogs: sometimes quietly playing in the house and other times playing chase in the backyard. He gets along with all of our resident dogs, both males and females.

Due to his size, children in the home should be over 8 years old.

This sweet boy needs a good-sized fence to keep him safe. He has a history of escaping and could easily jump a low fence if he wanted. He is also very skilled at trying to dash out an open door—like when you reach outside to bring in a box that was just delivered—he's got his eyes open for those quick opportunities. 

To learn more about Rokey, see his bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/rokey-15-058

Placement Requirements:
Good With Dogs: Yes
Good With Cats: Yes
Good With Kids:  8+
Fence: Physical fence required
Age: 6

If you are interested in any of the dogs available at Retrieve a Golden of the Midwest (RAGOM), you can read our adoption process and apply to adopt, which can be found at https://ragom.org/our-adoption-process. RAGOM’s adoption territory includes: Minnesota; Iowa; North Dakota; South Dakota; Western Wisconsin (within 75 miles of the Minnesota border)

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Annie!  I am a former Texas girl and they called me Granny back in the day but my foster family did not think that suited me as I am too energetic and playful.  I was picked up as a stray and was living on a property with a good Samaritan and the other rescued street dogs until I could get into rescue in Texas and finally to Wisconsin.  Initially I had some skin issues and sores but those have all been taken care of.  Next a had a whole lot of testing to make sure my organs were strong for a spay surgery.  Initially there was concern over my blood clotting ability and kidneys but repeated testing over time has proven with proper nutrition my body was able to get back on track and into the normal zone.  I will be spayed soon, then looking for my forever family.

     My foster family is home much of the time and it turns out, that is the best future for me.  I love people and attention but especially like to see where foster mom is at all times.  I have been around lots of dogs in Texas and in Wisconsin and I am very playful.  I like to wrestle, run, and snuggle with other dogs.  I have been around dogs and people of all sized but I don't seem to know my size and love to curl up on everyone, big and small, so that is something to watch out for. I like to sleep in a dog pile but will also go find my own spot if I am too squished.

     I have been a really fun addition to my foster home.  I can definitely run with my long legs and have plenty of energy left in me so a fenced yard would be very beneficial so i get my exercise in outdoors.  I love to go outside throughout the day but will bark to come in.  I am not as good at letting you know I want out so there were some accidents in the beginning but now mom takes me out whenever I get up from a nap or seem to be pacing about.  I do like to nap plenty during the day as well and can curl up into surprisingly small spaces.

     I am strong and pull ahead on a leash, so the kids in the family cannot walk me.  We will be trying to switch to a gentle leader as I will pull on a collar until I sound raspy.  I do love walking with the family and like to walk with mom so I know where she is.  I am not as comfortable in the car though and try to sit on mom's lap when she drives.  We are working on that as I am lanky and do not make an ideal window.  I love food but with my height it is important not to leave food on the counter.  I used to eat like every meal was my last and though I have settled down some, I still eat alone as I scarf what I have a look for more.  I am currently on grain free fish based food and over the counter antihistamine as I was scratching my belly for a while.  I am not anymore but no one really knows why so I'm not sure if I need to stay on those things.  Initially I would try to grab paper or toilet paper to chew up, which is likely I sign that I was often hungry in my past.  Now  I love chewing on toys and bones and that also keeps me busy. 

     That's kind of the basics.  I'm a pretty typical coonhound gal with plenty of goofy quirks that make me the loveable, long legged hound dog that I am.  If you think I may be the hound you need, you can fill out the adoption application under the Adoption heading on our website www.bassetbuddiesrescue.org and a volunteer will reach out to you.
animal.name: Annie

animal.description: Meet Little Man! Little Man may be small at 6-7 lbs, but boy does he have a BIG personality! His favorite thing to do is snuggle in your lap, followed by giving kisses and nibbling on your face. He is a true velcro dog who would love a family who is home often or willing to take him with them if they are out a lot. Little Man is great with other dogs (and cats!) and enjoys a daily play session. He’s easily excited and will dance for almost anything. We recommend a home with teenagers or no kids at all due to his small size. Little Man does great on a leash and in the car. He is a typical Chihuahua who is still working on house training but he does fairly well when he is able to go out often. He has the cutest little bark and tends to use his voice when left alone. We believe that he may have some allergies and is currently taking medications to help. If you love Little Man as much as we do, please apply at www.milehighcanine.org! He is in foster in Fort Collins and his adoption fee is $350. REQUIREMENTS: Lap/bed/couch privileges Family who is home often or will take him out with them (but not leave him in the car alone) Kids teenage+ or no kids due to his small size  You can apply for Little Man at https://milehighcanine.org/forms-and-applications/mhcr-adoption-application/.
animal.name: Little Man
